1. d4 f5 2. Qd3 $5 {This move looks to be combined with g4! and h3! ideas. Here we would rather go for a different approach as our usual answer (fxg4 and g3) works far worse as Qxg3 is an ideal square for the queen to attack.} (2. g4 {You can play almost anything against the Dutch. Yeah, precisely, ALMOST.} d5 {The Stonewall is a reliable friend in case of doubt.} 3. Nc3 (3. g5 c5 $15 {[%cal Ge7e6,Gb8c6,Gc8d7] We play somewhat like an advanced french and just pretend the kingside never happend.}) (3. gxf5 Bxf5 $15 {[%cal Ge7e6,Gg8f6,Gb8c6] We don't even need to do anything fancy. Think in a positive way, we got rid of the f5 pawn that always causes some trouble :).}) 3... Nf6 $15 4. g5 Ne4 $15 {[%cal Gc7c5] c5 or Nc6-e5 are likely the answers to any attempt.}) (2. h3 e6 $5 3. g4 d5 $11 {The thing is, black gets a lot of benefit of having the e-file open (even an extra square for the c8 bishop) so we are not mad about gxf5 exchange at all.}) (2. h4 {Modern chess, amirite? In this case, quite decent.} e6 $5 {Our beloved classical Dutch leaves white wondering what to do with the h4 pawn basically.} 3. Bg5 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Nbd2 O-O 6. Bxf6 Bxf6 7. e4 {This position appeared out of transposition a couple times by Indjic and Dubov.} c5 $5 $132 {[%cal Yf6b2] This forgotten move feels quite natural considering we have both bishops and the h4 pawn would be obviously bad the more the position opens out.0-1 (38) Winfridsson,O (2080)-Stone,A (2254) Coventry 2005}) (2. e3 {I likely to transpose to chapter 8 or 9 if White plays with Nc3 or Nf3 later on. So 2. ... Nf6 should be fine.}) 2... Nc6 {This very specific move works very well here.} 3. d5 (3. Nf3 e6 4. c4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Be7 $132 {[%cal Ge8g8,Yd7d6,Ye6e5,Ye7b4] We'll go for castle and later on d6-Qe8. Again plans with Nd8-Nf7 can happen. If White tries to get too much with the likes of Bf4-e3 we might even benefit now from Bb4!. I'd rather not do it with the darksquared bishop still on c1, as it will have a good comfort on b2 after a3-b4 and the bishop pair would be annoying there mid-long term.}) 3... Nb4 4. Qxf5 (4. Qd1 Nf6 5. c4 e6 {[%cal Gb4a6,Ga6c5] I mean, we developed 4 things, White 2 things, should be great. The knight will shift to c5 and later on d6-e5 would be the go-to.}) 4... Nf6 $11 {[%csl Gc2,Gd5,Rf5][%cal Gb4d5,Gb4c2,Gg7g6,Gd7d6,Gc8f5] The c2 pawn or the d5 pawn, White needs to choose between two evils and we are more than happy.} *

