{[%evp 0,26,28,28,69,-21,-21,-29,0,-32,6,-24,-18,-27,31,39,50,22,25,25,25,25,25,25,108,61,61,69,69]} 1. d4 f5 2. e4 {Writing this lines I realize I actually never faced the Staunton gambit in a game. It's not very common in higher levels as I only started playing the Dutch when I reached 2500. Can be tricky if you don't know but overall it's not a menace I'd say.} fxe4 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 {The main concern for black is not beeing able to realiable play d7-d5 due to Qh5+ or Bxf6+Qh5+. For instance against 3. f3 d5! would be good for black and later on we won't need to play g7-g6 to prepare d5.} (4. f3 d5 5. fxe4 dxe4 $1 {Be always weary of Qh5+!} 6. Bg5 Bf5 $1 {[%csl Ge4] As shown in the mainline, we don't want to transpose here with 6. ... g7-g6 as we wanted to enter this position with Nxe4! and also we just play g6 to be able to play d7-d5 and here we already did.} 7. Bc4 (7. Nge2 {This is not specially critical but I found some curious positions that you might enjoy.} e6 8. Ng3 Be7 9. Bb5+ {White typically does this check first as 9. ... Nc6! is a great answer to 9. Bc4.} Nc6 $1 {This funny novelty makes the whole thing easy to remember.} 10. Nxf5 exf5 11. d5 {[%cal Gb5e8,Gd5c6]} a6 {A very typical resource to solve the pin. We have plenty of examples like the Botvinnik variation with h6-g5 or the Armenia variation in the Winawer with a3-b4.} 12. Ba4 b5 13. Nxb5 axb5 14. Bxb5 O-O 15. Bxc6 (15. dxc6 Qe8 $132 {We have an excellent center and white position is so delicate. Just Kh8 and look for the weak dark squares might be a good approach. White has tons of useless pawns on the queenside. Only 16. Qe2 keeps the balance as the other moves lose.}) 15... Rb8 {[%cal Gb8b2]} 16. O-O {White cannot afford to defend b2.} Ng4 $15 {White position is so hard to defend. I'll give you a very nice example of our harmony.} 17. Bxe7 Qxe7 18. Qd4 {Looks nice as it defends b2 and c5+ but basically loses.} Qd6 19. g3 Qh6 20. h4 Rb4 $1 {[%csl Ge3][%cal Gh6e3] The rook is untouchable.} 21. Qc3 Rc4 $1 {[%cal Gc4c2] We won in a very nice fashion.}) 7... Nbd7 $1 {[%cal Gd7f6] With a couple precise moves we'll easily counter this popular approach from white.} 8. Nge2 h6 9. Bh4 g5 10. Bg3 c6 {[%cal Ge7e6,Gd8e7,Gf8g7,Gf5g6,Ge8g8] We dodge Nb5 and we will follow up with e6-Qe7-Bg6 (otherwise we can't castle as Rxf5! will be a threat) and white is helpless to regain the pawn or to create some counterplay.}) 4... g6 $5 {The old main line was Nc6, but this just works better. Our aim is to play d7-d5, not so much Bg7 yet.} 5. h4 {[%csl Re8][%cal Gh4h5] The Dutch, specially the Leningrad, is always connected to h2-h4-h5 threats. Since we have a weak e8-h5 diagonal, rook sacrifices after h5-Nxh5 are pretty comon.} (5. Bxf6 exf6 6. Nxe4 d5 $15 {We'll look for Nc6 and long castle. White gave up the bishop pair for free and our extended pawn structures covers all the weak spots in blacks position.}) (5. Bc4 {This might be the most challenging move. Unsurprinsingly it happens as White prevents us from play d7-d5. I realized black has a very clever way to achieve the forementioned goal.} c6 6. d5 {Usually this move discouraged black to aim for d5. White blocks the option and basically paralizes our position while completing the development. It was even what I had in mind years ago and this position performs very well in practice for white. But we have a very nice surprise.} Bg7 7. Nge2 e6 $1 {We change the nature of the position. White was aiming for a practical position and suddenly we force them to take inmediate reaction.} 8. Nxe4 (8. d6 {[%csl Rd6] This move usually would mean problems. But we have a way to develop every piece around it and it kinda ressembles the twoknights variation in the sicilian, were white manages to play e4-e5 and then Nd6+.} O-O {[%csl Ga5][%cal Gd8a5] Tecnically 8. ... Qa5 is a bit more precise but the line is so specific that I don't want you to waste your precious memory on this. We aim for Qa5 and then b6 or b5 to free the c8 bishop. Not having the f7 pawn changes quite a lot the perspective of this position as the f file is for us to enjoy while the a2-g8 diagonal is not weak at all. We are likely to transpose to 8. Nxe4.}) 8... O-O $1 {Taking the pawn might be a bit too optimistic but this move allows us to play d7-d5 and consolidate our position.} 9. dxe6 (9. d6 $5 {White can mix both ideas but we solve it in a similar fashion.} Qa5+ 10. Bd2 {We don't mind 10. Qd2 as exchanging the queens and following up with b5! gives us enough room to finish developing.} Qe5 11. Nxf6+ Qxf6 $132 {[%cal Gf6f2,Gf6b2,Gb7b6,Gc8b7] This is the "engine" sequence. As f2 and b2 are hanging, here you have two paths. 1. The path of the brave (could be foolish or could bring glory to your family name)Taking the b2 pawn and defending well or 2. Just finishing development with b6-Bb7 and chill.}) 9... d5 10. O-O Bxe6 11. Bb3 Nbd7 $11 {[%cal Ge6f7,Gc6c5] After some fireworks the smoke vanishes and we are left with an excellent position. ½-½ (31) Ziese,G (2484)-Wenzel,S (2461) ICCF email 2018}) (5. f3 d5 $1 {Of course.} 6. fxe4 {Now giving up the bishop pair with 6. Bxf6 would be even worse considering how open is the position now.} Nxe4 $1 {[%cal Yg7d4,Yf8f1,Gb8c6,Gf8g7] Taking with the pawn might mean suffering after Qd2-0-0-0 and a long game ahead. We want to create some fast pressure on d4 and also use the f file in our benefit.} 7. Nxe4 dxe4 8. Bc4 Nc6 $15 {[%cal Gc6a5] It's very important to have the Nc6-Na5 idea in mind, as sometimes we would require it to castle. Black is completely fine and White doesn't is too slow to finish development.}) 5... d5 {Obviously} 6. h5 Bf5 {Taking on h5 would also mean losing the d5 pawn in both cases.} 7. Bxf6 exf6 8. g4 {[%cal Yh1h8] Only sensible way to progress. White makes use of the pin.} Be6 9. hxg6 Qd7 {We have superior development, superior center, bishop pair. White needs to create quick threats or we will steamroll the position.} 10. g5 {[%cal Gd1h5] White aims for Qh5} Qg7 $1 {[%cal Gg7g6] We want to take g6 so basically we force white move.} 11. Qh5 {We are still following ½-½ (25) Nyzhnyk,I (2679)-Stremavicius,T (2484) Dulles 2021} Nd7 {[%cal Ge8c8] I deviate from mainstream games as this move order feels a bit more logical as we are close to finish development and we keep more pieces otb.} 12. gxf6 Nxf6 13. Qe5 Qe7 $132 {[%cal Ge8c8,Gc7c6,Gf8g7] We will finish up the rest of the development and White is left with tons of options but no real clear way to go. Let them think, let them sink.} *

