1. d4 f5 2. Bg5 {This might be one the most challenging moves. White creates an annoying pin and also wants to pressure quickly our weakened Kingside. I even played it in my win against Wesley So back in 2004, so it is a well known approach.} g6 $5 {This has been played by Anton, Lagarde, Kamsky, Bartel and more recently Sadhwani maybe the strongest players that recently relied on the Dutch. Black prioritizes development and looks for reactions on the center.} (2... h6 {There is a funny trend with this line as it is the correspondence option.} 3. Bh4 {It is well known that White can afford to "trap" the bishop as e2-e3 threatens mate and basically prevents black from capturing the bishop with h6-g5-f4.} g5 4. e3 Bg7 5. Bg3 c5 6. c3 Qb6 {If you are a machine it might make sense to go for it, but as a human this is just a London were black went crazy and will need to play with precision for tons of moves as the position is incredibly weak and exposed. Here for instance 7. Na3! solves all the problems in b2 and leaves White with a great position.}) 3. Nc3 {[%cal Re2e4] White plays in a similar fashion as if it was a Sicilian.} (3. e3 Bg7 4. Nd2 {The only move order left to cover.} (4. h4 {This combination of moves gets quickly punished. 4. Nf3 gets a similar treatment.} h6 5. Bf4 d6 $132 {[%cal Gb8c6,Gg8f6] We have many examples of great transpositions to Leningrad-ish dutch. I want to point out how Bd7 later on sometimes helps to annoy white with Na5! if Bc4 happens to be on the board.} 6. c4 Nf6 {Got an excellent position out of the opening. I'd say 6. ... Nd7! was even stronger and e7-e5 is coming switfly. 1-0 (35) Costachi,M (2463)-Alonso Rosell,A (2570) Warsaw 2021}) (4. Nf3 h6 {Now this move is safe and if feels like an odd London.} 5. Bh4 {Only reasonable move to make it challenging, teasing us to play g6-g5.} d6 (5... Nf6 $6 6. Bxf6 $5 {This is what the engines says, why are you looking at me like that?} Bxf6 7. Nc3 $14 {[%csl Rg6][%cal Ge3e4,Gc3e2,Ge2f4,Gh2h4] Seems we have weakened our light squares with the free h6 so it might be tricky to hace h4-Ne2 after we go for 7. ... d5 to prevent e3-e4.}) 6. c4 g5 7. Bg3 e6 {This is such a bizarre position. We want to play like a Hippopotamus} 8. Nc3 Ne7 $1 $132 {[%cal Gb8c6,Ge8g8,Ye6e5,Gb8d7,Gb7b6,Gc8b7] e6-e5 would be easier to play later on. The key idea is that playing 8. ... Nf6 we have a risky version of the London with that extended kingside and we give black some extra ideas.}) 4... Nc6 {Here almost any move makes sense as Nd2 is not specially critical. 4. ... Nh6!? even was interesting. Feel free to experiment with the dutch!} 5. c3 {Basically not playing h2-h4 and shifting to a London-esque position is the best White can do here.} Nf6 6. Ngf3 e6 $5 {To prevent d4-d5 in case of 6. ... d6 and going for h6-d6 looks very good for black.}) (3. Nd2 Bg7 {And now e3 or e4 transpose.}) 3... Bg7 (3... d5 {This alternative plan is a bit worse in general. I beat Wesley so almost 20 years ago with White but it has a decent charm to it so i'll put a recent game of mine if you want to consider it.} 4. e3 Bg7 5. h4 c6 {We want to delay Nf6 as h4-h5 would be the answer. Now white cannot push h4-h5 yet as we can go with h6-g5 and efficiently close the kingside.} 6. Bd3 Qb6 7. Rb1 Nd7 $132 {[%cal Ge7e5]} 8. Nf3 e5 9. dxe5 Nxe5 10. Nxe5 Bxe5 11. h5 Be6 $6 (11... Qc7 $1 $132 {[%cal Gh7h6,Gg5f4,Ge5f4]}) 12. Ne2 $16 {0-1 (34) Sychev,K (2550)-Alonso Rosell, A (2570) Warsaw 2021}) 4. e4 {The most played move but not the best.} (4. e3 Nh6 $5 {[%cal Gh6f7] This creative idea works well here. Eventually we want to go for Nf7 and strike in the center. 4. ... c6!? could be a mover order to consider equally.} 5. h4 {[%cal Rh4h5]} (5. Bc4 c6 {[%cal Gd7d5] Here it looks more logical to just aim for stonewall-ish positions. We can appreciate the similarities between this position and some stonewalls where Black goes for Nh6 directly to control the e5 square later.} 6. f4 {This funny idea was tried recently in a clash of young indian talents. White wants to prevent e7-e5 once and for all. But i'd say it makes it easy for us to take the decision to do a stonewall.} (6. Qd2 {This novelty has a smart trick in mind.} d5 7. e4 $1 {[%csl Rh6]} dxc4 8. Bxh6 Qxd4 9. Bxg7 Qxg7 10. O-O-O $44 {White has some compensation thanks to our "curious" pawn structure but our next moves are quite simple: 0-0, b5, bishop out, Na6 so I wouldn't bother that much.}) 6... d5 (6... b5 7. Bd3 d6 $5 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gc8b7,Gd7f6] Could be a creative way to face this position. Our setup is kinda similar to a Modern defense and can definetely confuse White.}) 7. Bd3 Nf7 8. Bh4 $132 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gd7f6,Gf6e4] The knight is coming to e4 and White doesn't really know what to do with the c3 knight. Later on we might go for h6-g5 or some expansion on the queenside.}) 5... c6 {This smart move has really good results, here we want to bait h4-h5.} 6. h5 (6. Qf3 {This is the preferred move by the engine, it looks a bit weird, I guess White aims to an eventual control of the e7-e5 breakthrough with Qg3-Nf3. I'd say it's a relative success if White needs to adapt so much from conventional plans.} Nf7 7. O-O-O {Another engine move. Taking on g5 would make it easy for white as Qg3-Nf3 and focusing h7 would be a very annoying setup.} (7. Bf4 d6 {[%cal Gb8d7,Ge7e5] We'll play Nd7 and e5 and I don't see what's wrong with our position.}) 7... d5 $132 {[%csl Rf3][%cal Gb8d7] We'll likely be able to play e5 or just Nd7-Nf6 and even follow up with b7-b5 and an attack on the queenside.}) 6... Nf7 7. h6 Bf8 8. Bf4 e6 $132 {[%csl Rh1,Rh6][%cal Gd7d5,Gb8d7,Gf8e7,Ge8g8] The pawn on h6 doesn't really do much and we'll peacefully go for d5-Be7-Nd7-0-0 and eventually push for e6-e5. Having the knight on c3 really slows down White in controling the whole board.}) (4. h4 Nc6 {[%cal Gc6d4] I prefer this move over 4. ... h6 as White's play is very straightforward after 5. Bf4 and e2-e4.} 5. d5 (5. Nf3 h6 6. Bf4 d6 {[%cal Ge7e5]} 7. e4 {I was a bit puzzled as against 7. Qd3 apparently the best move was 7. ... a6!. The reasoning behind is, as usual, our opponents threat! Which is d4-d5 and we wish to answer with Nb4 so we get ahead of Qb5+ that would be fatal! Isn't it chess lovely?} fxe4 8. Nxe4 e5 $1 {[%csl Gc6,Gf3] This is why including Nc6 and Nf3 makes a huge difference!} 9. dxe5 Bf5 $132 {[%cal Gd6e5] Will take on e5 and i'd say black is more than comfortable here and our play is pretty easy from now on.}) 5... Ne5 6. Nf3 $5 (6. e4 d6 $132 {[%cal Gc7c6,Gd8b6] We have a pseudo pirc where we force d5-d6 and the pawn on f5 gives some needed extra pressure into the center while it also gives squares to the e5 knight. We actually have 2 wins here with black!}) 6... d6 {Taking on f3 wouldn't be appropiate after exf3 and White would easily put us into problems after Bc4-Qe2 and rooks to the center. White looks for opening files in general.} 7. Nxe5 dxe5 {Usually this wouldn't be advised, as e2-e4 is really harmfull usually, but here works beautifully. The more patterns and resources you got, the better to enjoy the shifting nature of the Dutch!} 8. h5 {White would LOVE to play e2-e4 to kill the g7 bishop but here was countered by f4! and the bishop on g5 was trapped.} e4 $5 $132 {[%cal Gh7h6,Gg6g5,Yg8h6,Ga7a6,Gd8d6,Gc8d7] We negated Whites attack and we have plenty of room for the rest of our pieces. A plan like a6-Qd6-Bd7 would grant us a good control of both light and dark squares.}) (4. Nf3 {Our beloved engine has some surprises with this move.} Nf6 (4... h6 $2 {I mean this move looks logical and has a great score but basically loses if White knows what he's doing.} 5. Bf4 Nf6 {[%csl Ge4] We need to prevent e2-e4.} 6. Nh4 $1 (6. h4 d6 $132 {[%cal Gb8c6,Ge8g8,Ge7e5] And we have an excellent version of the Leningrad where White didn't achieve anything special.}) 6... Kf7 7. e4 $1 fxe4 8. f3 $1 $18 {If your opponent blitzes this I have very bad news for you. In general, I'd say it is very weird someone could find this OTB so you can be smart about it, but be careful out there!}) 5. Bxf6 (5. e3 d5 $1 {[%cal Gf6e4,Gc7c5] Might be a bit confusing to face each move order considering sometimes we play Nh6 or we delay d5 but I hope eventually it all makes sense to you! Now we want to go for Ne4-c5 as a good counter.} 6. Bd3 (6. Bf4 {This move scored very well in correspondence chess and it was mentioned by Roiz. White threatens Nb5 and c2-c4.} c6 7. Bd3 O-O 8. O-O Ne4 9. Ne2 {[%cal Gc2c4] As we said in many occasions white wants to go for c2-c4.} Be6 $5 {This peculiar setup was popularized by Mateusz Bartel on his own and I fondly remember playing it in bullet when I was 10, so many easy moves to play fast! White has perfect control of the dark squares but we keep some presence in the light squares.} 10. Rc1 (10. Be5 Bh6 $5 $146 {Makes more sense to avoid exchanging the bishops.} (10... Bf6 {A correspondence game followed like this but doesn't make that much sense to me. I see black wants to recapture with the e pawn and cover the e5 square, but the outcome is not precisely exciting.} 11. Rc1 Nd7 12. c4 Bf7 13. Bxf6 exf6 14. c5 a5 15. a3 a4 16. Nc3 Qa5 17. Na2 Qc7 18. g3 b6 19. cxb6 Nxb6 20. Nd2 Rfc8 21. Nb4 Qd6 22. Qe2 Kg7 23. Rfd1 h5 24. h4 c5 25. dxc5 Rxc5 26. Rxc5 Qxc5 27. Kg2 Ra7 28. Nf3 Nc4 29. Nd4 Qc8 30. Rc1 {1/2-1/2 (30) Lakudas,A (2420)-Oliynyk,V (2327) ICCF email 2020}) 11. h3 {White gets ahead of Nd7.} Nd7 12. Bh2 Re8 $5 {[%cal Ge7e5] We eventually want to play e7-e5 so it is a decently useful move.} (12... Bg7 $6 13. Nf4 $1 Bf7 14. Bxe4 $1 dxe4 15. Ng5 $1 $16 {[%csl Ge6] It's an annoying sequence.}) 13. Rc1 {[%cal Gc2c4]} (13. b3 {[%cal Gc2c4]} Bg7 14. c4 Rc8 {[%cal Ge6f7,Yc6c5,Ye7e5] According to engine White is very happy but doesn't seem obvious to me. At least we have a couple ideas with Bf7 and c5 or e5 depending on what White plays.}) 13... Bg7 {Now we can answer Ng5 idea with e5! and e6 square is covered.} 14. c4 dxc4 15. Bxc4 Bxc4 {Exchanging this bishop is a huge difference.} 16. Rxc4 e6 $14 {[%csl Rf5][%cal Ga8c8,Gc6c5,Ga7a6,Gb7b5] White can claim a small strucutural advantage but we have a plan with c5-a6-b5. We can also choose to turtle up with a6 and Rc8 and wait for our opportunity. Reminds me of the slav with g6 and a position where Chinese players would excel.}) 10... Nd7 11. c4 dxc4 12. Bxc4 Bxc4 {Again exchanging this bishop is some kind of a relief.} 13. Rxc4 Qa5 $5 $14 {[%cal Ge7e5,Ga5d5] We have e7-e5 option and also Qd5-Rfc8-c5. Obviously having the f5 pawn is punishing in terms of flexibility but considering this might be the most precise try for white, i'm decently happy.}) 6... Ne4 7. Bf4 c5 $1 8. Nb5 O-O $5 {This move surprisingly works very well. After 8. ... Na6 ? we get a typical position out of the Jobava London but a far worse version without any control of the center. Black was busted in ½-½ (58) Ma,Z (2468)-Lu,S (2570) China 2015} 9. O-O (9. Nc7 e5 $1 $17 {[%csl Rc7] And the knight would not live to see another day.}) 9... c4 10. Nc7 {It's very hard, humanwise, to appreciate that now Nc7 is far far better than before.} e5 11. Nxe5 Qxc7 12. Bxe4 fxe4 13. Nxg6 Qf7 $132 {[%csl Gd5,Ge4][%cal Gb8c6] We have very good control of the light squares and it is quite unlikely we ever reach here. But oh well, people nowadays get very creative with their preps. ½-½ (42) Simal Moreira,L (2362)-Sanchez,M (2319) ICCF email 2017}) 5... Bxf6 {Taking with the pawn would be dramatic after 6. d5! and our bishops would be doomed.} 6. e4 fxe4 7. Nxe4 d5 8. Nxf6+ (8. Ned2 $6 {White got a terrible position after 1-0 (42) Grandelius,N (2663)-Asis Gargatagli,H (2470) Chess.com INT 2020} O-O $17 {[%cal Gc7c5,Gb8c6,Ge7e5] and c5-Nc6-e5 would conquer the world.}) 8... exf6 $132 {[%cal Gb8c6,Ge8g8,Gg8g7,Gc8e6] We have a very solid position and the f6,g6 pawnchain give us good coverage. Going for Nc6-Be6 and even Qd6 would be the perfect setup. There we could even choose to castle long if White gets too creative.}) 4... fxe4 5. Nxe4 d5 $1 {We strike the center.} 6. Nc3 (6. Ng3 $5 {Looks weird as the knight doesn't have any good jumps but has a very nice idea.} c5 $1 {Since the b1 knight abandoned the queenside, it makes sense to pressure it a bit.} (6... Nh6 $6 7. Nh5 $1 gxh5 8. Bxh6 $1 $16 {[%csl Re5,Rh5] Since we cannot take on h6 due to Qxh5+, our pawn structure is awful and we are left with a very ugly position.}) 7. Nf3 Nc6 8. dxc5 (8. c3 {Holding the center had very good success in practice but with a couple precise moves we should be more than fine.} cxd4 9. Nxd4 Nxd4 10. cxd4 Qb6 $15 {[%csl Gb2,Gd4,Rg3][%cal Gb6d4,Gb6b2] With this simple improvement we prevent Bb5+ and we might take a pawn. The knight on g3 is completely out of place and we have easy development ahead.} (10... Qa5+ 11. Bd2 Qb6 12. Bc3 {White managed to rearrange better its pieces and the e5 square control decided.} Nf6 13. Be2 O-O 14. O-O Ne4 15. Nxe4 dxe4 16. Qb3+ Be6 17. Bc4 Bxc4 18. Qxc4+ Kh8 19. Rae1 Rf4 20. g3 Rg4 21. h3 Rg5 22. Rxe4 Bf6 23. Rfe1 Qd6 24. R1e3 Rd5 25. Bb4 Qd7 26. Bxe7 Bg7 27. Bc5 Bf6 28. Re6 Bxd4 29. Re7 Rxc5 30. Qf7 Rc1+ 31. Kh2 {1-0 (31) Yuffa,D (2566)-Sethuraman,S (2638) Moscow 2019})) 8... Bxb2 9. Rb1 Bc3+ 10. Bd2 Qa5 {[%csl Gd5,Ge7] This is a somewhat old variation. We have Aronian and Nikolic showing off in 2003!. Black has the center but it is a bit behind in development so we need to play quick to avoid beeing conquered.} 11. Bb5 Nf6 12. O-O Bxd2 13. Nxd2 O-O 14. c4 $1 {[%cal Rc4d5]} a6 15. Bxc6 bxc6 16. cxd5 Qxc5 $1 $132 {[%cal Ga8a7,Ga7c7] With this simple improvement It is not really difficult to defend this position. We might have presence in the a8-h1 diagonal and shifting the rook to c7 might help to defend our weakest point (e7) and also provide flexbility to the c8 bishop.} (16... cxd5 17. Qc2 $16 Bd7 18. Rfe1 Rfe8 19. Nf3 Rac8 20. Rbc1 Ba4 21. Qe2 Rxc5 22. Rxc5 Qxc5 23. Qxa6 Bd7 24. h3 Rb8 {1/2-1/2 (24) Aronian,L (2649)-Nikolic,P (2647) Germany 2003})) (6. Nc5 $5 {This creative move aims for an ideal world playing Nb3-Nf3-Bf4-Bg3 and controling all our holes in dark squares.} b6 7. Nb3 Nf6 {After some investigation I figured we are in time to push for e7-e5 "normally" with 0-0, Nc6, Qd6.} 8. Nf3 O-O 9. Be2 Nc6 {[%cal Gd8d6,Ge7e5]} 10. Bh4 Nh5 $132 {[%csl Gf4][%cal Gg7f6,Gh5f4,Ge7f6] It's lovely how we control plenty of dark squares in a matter of 5-6 moves. Now Bf6 would be great to kill the h4 bishop and then look for Nf4 or use the weak squares to flow with the c8 bishop after g2-g3.}) 6... Nh6 $1 {[%cal Gh6f7] We look for Nf7 and an eventual e7-e5.} 7. Nf3 (7. Qd2 Nf7 8. Be3 c5 $1 {[%cal Gb8c6] It is a great extra option as White cannot take due to d5-d4. Black is already better.} 9. Nf3 Nc6 10. Bb5 O-O 11. Bxc6 bxc6 $19 {[%cal Ge7e5,Yc5d4] 0-1 (52) Kalashian,D (2398)-Howell,D (2646) Chess.com INT 2022}) 7... Nc6 {Makes more sense to just go for Nf7 after we are teased with Qd2.} 8. Qd2 Nf7 9. Be3 Bf5 $132 {[%cal Gd8d7,Ge8c8] We will follow this great game from Kamsky. Black has perfect control of the e5 square and bascially after castling long will slowly prepare the expansion on the center while doesn't really have any clear plan.} 10. Be2 Qd7 11. O-O-O O-O-O 12. Kb1 Kb8 13. a3 h6 14. h3 g5 15. g4 Be6 16. Rhe1 Rhf8 17. Nh2 Nd6 18. f3 Bg8 19. Nb5 a6 20. Nxd6 Qxd6 21. Nf1 e5 22. dxe5 Qxe5 23. c3 d4 24. cxd4 Qd5 {0-1 (24) Pardo Simon,D (2451)-Kamsky,G (2709) Caleta 2014} *

