1. d4 f5 2. Bf4 $5 {The London way is quite a good answer to the Dutch. I remember having issues in friendly games to counter the go-to setup with Nf3-e3-Be2-h3-Bh2 and then c4-c5 push. I got a good victory against Zoltan Medvegy with black some years ago but definetely feels like a completely different variation.} Nf6 3. e3 d6 {As I said before, it requires certain precision. 3. ... e6 could be fine, i'll add an idea of it because I think it is instructure, but overall I feel this is more consistent and we basically only rely on e7-e6 is is needed. We need to know that 3. ... g6 is just bad thanks to 4. h4!.} (3... e6 {This plan you'll see here could also be a good way to face this position. We pay White with the same coin and we do a no-brainer plan that works well as a blueprint.} 4. Nf3 g6 5. c4 Bg7 6. Nc3 d6 7. Be2 O-O 8. O-O Qe7 9. h3 Nc6 10. Bh2 Nd8 11. Rc1 Nf7 {[%cal Gb8c6,Gc6d8,Gd8f7]} 12. c5 Bd7 13. b4 g5 14. Nd2 Kh8 15. a4 {Until here both players were almost perfect and it truly shows how easy is to get steamrolled with black as White plan is very straighforward. Now Rad8 followed by e5 might be the best plan.} Rg8 16. Nb5 Bc6 17. Nc4 f4 18. Na5 a6 19. Nc3 Bh6 20. Bg4 Nxg4 21. hxg4 e5 22. Re1 Bg7 23. exf4 gxf4 24. Bxf4 Qf6 25. Nxc6 bxc6 26. Bg3 {White was crushing but black incredibly managed to save it. 1/2-1/2 (58) Le,Q (2739) -Idani,P (2566) Ashkhabad 2017}) 4. Nf3 (4. Nc3 {White can mess around with this move order. We cover in this chapter as we play without d6 usually.} e6 {4. ... g6 here doesn't work really well after 5. h4! and Qf3!} 5. Nf3 (5. h3 {[%cal Gg2g4] This was suggested in Lifetime Repertoires: Sahaj and Srinath's London System} Nc6 $1 {[%cal Gd8e7,Gc8d7] I give this new move. We want to switch the plan playing Bd7-Qe7-0-0-0. This way g2-g4 is far less effective.} 6. g4 Qe7 {[%cal Ge6e5]} 7. gxf5 (7. Qf3 {This is an example if White wants to be ambitious.} e5 8. Bg5 fxg4 9. hxg4 Bxg4 $1 10. Qg2 exd4 11. Nd5 Qf7 $132) (7. Bg2 g6 $5 {[%cal Gc8d7,Gf8g7,Gc6d8,Gd8f7,Gg6f5] We have a very nice maneouvring position.}) 7... e5 $1 {And black is already better.}) (5. Bd3 Nc6 $132) 5... Nc6 {We cannot relax and allow White to play Bd3-e4.} 6. Bd3 {Otherwise we can just follow with g6 or h6 and eventually look for e6-e5, as always.} Nb4 $5 $132 {Our knight will go to d5 and we can complete the development with Be7-0-0. White is left without a plan and we have very easy moves going forward. It is likely that some kind of stonewall arises with an extra pawn on d6 covering the e5 outpost!}) 4... g6 5. c4 {I'd say this is the most fearsome way to play. Imagine a world were London players adapt and improve the setup while playing it, not mindlessly spamming the first 15 moves every game, damn scary right?} (5. Bc4 {This is one of the cases were we are forced to play e6.} e6 6. O-O Bg7 7. h3 O-O $132 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Gg8h8,Gb8c6,Gd8e7] We'll go with the same plan and, at the end of the day, White would've lost a tempo with Bc4.}) (5. h3 {Let's say white does the "I don't care what you play" plan.} Bg7 6. Be2 O-O 7. O-O Nc6 8. Bh2 {Alex Banzea's London System} Kh8 $1 {I love giving small ideas here and there so you get more creative. Here we want to go for Qe8-e5 .In case of 9. c3, we don't want to allow b4-b5 easily so we also want to play quickly e5-e4 so then the knight can reroute through e7-d5 or g6 after g6-g5. Another good advice would be to take on e5 with the c6 knight whenever there is a pawn on c3. This simple idea applies even to the Italian, the knight gets countered and will be targetted so we better exchange it.} 9. c4 e5 $1 {Bear in mind we also don't want to allow white to make too much progress with Nc3-Nd5 ideas so, again, we need to be quick.} 10. dxe5 Ne4 $132 {[%cal Yg7b2] And we have an excellent center and a great position.}) 5... Bg7 6. Nc3 O-O 7. Be2 {Not playing h2-h3 is useful as Nh5 doesn't really threaten Nxf4, as white would get an excellent control of the center and e7-e5 would be hard to do.} (7. c5 Kh8 {It's funny how Mamedyarov played this with black and got a great position and a couple weeks later went into losing with White!} 8. Bc4 {Looks like the most serious attempt.} (8. h4 Be6 $15 {Suddenly White has a sever lack of presence on light squares.} 9. Qa4 Qd7 10. Bb5 c6 11. Be2 Bg8 12. Rd1 b5 $5 13. cxb6 Qb7 {Great thematic sacrifice, all black pieces point into the queenside/center.} 14. Ng5 axb6 15. Qc2 Nbd7 16. h5 Nxh5 17. Bxh5 gxh5 18. Bg3 Nf6 19. a3 c5 20. d5 Nxd5 21. Ne2 Nf6 $19 {0-1 (42) Mamedyarov,S (2756)-Anton Guijarro,D (2614) Moscow 2015}) 8... Nc6 9. h4 {Now it makes more sense to create space for the bishop and threaten the kingside. H5 isn't really a threat right now, but definetely has to be taken care of.} (9. O-O Ne4 10. cxd6 cxd6 $132 {[%cal Ge7e5] Lars Oskar Hauge, a Dutch lover (he even plays it with white!) won already a couple games in this position. We have a very easy plan going forward, play e7-e5. We could also shift the approach and look for Nxc3, bxc3 and Bd7-Rc8-Na5 ideas.} 11. d5 Nxc3 12. bxc3 Ne5 13. Bxe5 dxe5 $15 {0-1 (67) Agrest,E (2574)-Hauge,L (2483) chess24.com INT 2020}) 9... h6 10. Ng5 (10. h5 {Be careful as white has lots of pieces pointing the kingside so some fireworks might be on the menu. It doesn't work for White but will serve as an example.} Nxh5 11. Bxh6 Bxh6 12. Nh4 Rf6 13. Nxg6+ Rxg6 14. Qxh5 Kg7 15. g4 $1 fxg4 16. Bd3 Qe8 17. Nd5 Qf7 18. f4 $5 {White just went all-in for 10 moves, but we are doing fine and we will end up in a 2piece + rookpawn endgame. The following line it's just some flashy enjoyable line I saw and couldn't resist to add :).} dxc5 $132 19. Nxc7 cxd4 20. Bxg6 Qxg6 21. Qxg6+ Kxg6 22. Nxa8 dxe3 $1 $132 {Funnily white is forced to give back a rook and black is more than fine.}) 10... Nh5 11. Nf7+ Rxf7 12. Bxf7 Nxf4 13. exf4 Nxd4 $132 {Black had an excellent compensation through the black squares and the center pawnchain.} 14. h5 g5 $1 15. fxg5 dxc5 $1 16. g6 Qd6 $15 {[%cal Gc8d7,Ge7e5] 1-0 (53) Ragger,M (2658)-Henrichs,T (2492) Germany 2015}) (7. h3 {This might be used as an example of how creative you can get with the Dutch.} c5 {7. ... Nc6 should be more than fine but this spicy move works decent here.} 8. d5 (8. Bd3 Nc6 {[%cal Gf6h5,Ge7e5] Followed by Nh5-e5 looks very spicy. If 9. d5 Nb4 and Ne4 give great counterplay.}) 8... b5 $5 {We have an incredible Benko. F5 played and a useless bishop on f4.} 9. Nxb5 (9. cxb5 Ne4 $132 {[%cal Yg7b2]}) 9... Ne4 $15 {[%csl Rb5][%cal Gd8a5] After Qa5+ and a6 White is already much worse}) (7. Bd3 $6 {It's extremely risky as an eventual e5-e4 wins a piece and e3-e4 is not an option with this setup.} Nc6 {[%cal Gf6h5,Ge7e5] Followed by Nh5-e5 or Qe8-e5 should be excellent.}) 7... Nc6 $5 8. Bg3 {This was suggested in Lifetime Repertoires: London System by Le Quang as 8. 0-0 Ne4! and e7-e5 is coming.} (8. O-O Ne4 9. Nxe4 fxe4 10. Nd2 Nxd4 $1 {That's why 8. Bg3 is smart.}) 8... Qe8 9. O-O e5 10. c5 {[%csl Gc5,Gd4,Ge3] White usually aims to crack the dark squares. I feel this move order is not likely to happen (usually White spends h2-h3 as a habit).} Ne4 $1 {[%cal Yg7c3] Another thematic idea.} 11. cxd6 cxd6 12. Rc1 Kh8 {[%cal Yb3g8] A useful move to prevent 13. b4 or issues later on with intermediate checks.} 13. Re1 Nxg3 14. hxg3 e4 15. Nd2 $132 {[%csl Rg3][%cal Ga8b8,Ge8d8,Gh7h5,Gh5h4] I would use Le Quang lines: "This position is complex with chances for both sides. White is slightly better on the queenside, while Black has potential with the bishop pair. I feel that it is easier to play for White though thanks to our control in the center. The plan is to play for Qb3, a4, Nc4." We could go for Rb8-Qd8-h5-h4 and we have an easier experience. The c8 bishop can shift to e8 later on.} *

