{[%evp 0,77,12,27,83,76,69,69,65,62,67,49,66,61,70,54,35,25,5,5,-7,-10,-1,0,0,-19,-4,-23,-13,-50,-45,-74,-43,-37,-28,-52,-67,-73,-81,-75,-38,-40,0,-21,-15,-21,0,-36,-23,-27,-26,-25,-8,-12,-14,-21,-14,-37,-28,-20,-38,-35,-43,-41,-47,-52,-47,-37,-38,0,0,0,-13,-13,-22,-34,-20,-1018,-1018,-1523]} 1. d4 f5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bg5 (3. e4 fxe4 {Transponses}) (3. Nf3 e6 {[%cal Gf8b4]} 4. a3 $5 d5 {[%cal Gc7c5,Ga7a6,Gb8d7] Followed by c5-a6 looks logical.}) 3... d5 4. e3 {This calm approach just wants to enjoy the dark squares we left unattended. Retreating the c3 knight and going for c2-c4 is usually the conventional plan.} e6 5. Nf3 (5. g4 {We solve this shenanigans the same way as if 2.Nc3 3.Bf4 4. g4 line.} fxg4 6. h3 g3 $15 {[%cal Gc7c5]}) 5... Nbd7 {I might be the only one having games with both colours here :). Black looks to go for c7-c5 quickly and stop whites idea to go for Ne2 and c4.} 6. Bd3 (6. Be2 $5 {Is a tricky way to play. Usually white goes for Bd3-Ne2-c4 (I even played it with white myself) . Here White is just happy with the London-ish stonewall.} Be7 $1 {I prefer this concrete approach, now that white cannot shift the c3 knight properly.} 7. O-O h6 $146 8. Bf4 (8. Bxf6 {Engine tends to like giving up the bishop pair, as it often likes it in closed-ish positions like some kings indian, but for humans is a nut really hard to crack and also a bit unappealing.} Bxf6 9. Nb1 c6 10. c4 O-O $132 {[%cal Gf6e7,Ge7d6,Yg7g5,Yf8f7] We'll shift the bishop to d6 and surely start pushing on the kingside. We would need a very cold-blooded person with white to enjoy this.}) 8... g5 9. Bg3 O-O {[%cal Gf6e4] We are actually threatening Ne4, dxe4, f4 so our opponent might want to do something about it.} 10. h3 a6 $1 $132 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Gb7b6,Gc7c5,Gc8b7,Ye7d6,Yd8e7,Ye7g7] We'll keep up with b6-Bb7 and we have an excellent stonewall as all our pieces come into play. Later on we might go for Bd6 idea and some pressure on the kingside through Qe7-Qg7.}) 6... c5 7. dxc5 $6 (7. O-O $5 {[%cal Gb2b3,Gc2c4] This engine-ish move has some evil into it. If we don't manage to expand on the queenside, White would have a very good advantage is c2-c4 ever happens. The f5 pawn is really good to control the center, but not as good if the position gets too open and out of control, as we need to asume c7-c5 has some risks aswell.} a6 (7... c4 8. Be2 Bb4 9. Nb1 b5 $5 (9... Qa5 10. a4 $14 {[%cal Ra7a6,Rb7b5] And Black never gets to play a6-b5 chaining everything. Bf4 will follow or Nbd2 if b5 is tried. Our card pyramid starts to shake.} (10. c3 Bd6 11. b3 b5 12. a4 Ne4 13. Bf4 $14 {[%csl Ge5] Gave me a pleasant edge in ½-½ (34) Alonso Rosell,A (2572)-Lagarde,M (2648) Chalons en Champagne 2021}) 10... b5) (9... a6 10. a4 Qc7 11. c3 Bd6 12. b3 $16 {Was terrible for black in: 0-1 (34) Mollah Abdullah,A (2472)-Anton Guijarro,D (2640) Al Ain 2015})) 8. b3 {Was a really clever idea from Tamir Nabaty} (8. a4 h6 9. Bh4 g5 10. Bg3 Nh5 $132 {We might even want to go for Nxg3 and h5!. This is definetely a funny position.}) 8... h6 $5 $146 (8... b5 {Looks convincing but black still has some problems as we will see in the game.} 9. a4 c4 10. Be2 b4 (10... Bb4 11. Na2 Bd6 12. axb5 axb5 13. Nc3 Ba6 (13... Rb8 14. Bf4 $14 {[%csl Ge5] Can be holdable for black but looks so sad how we have basically 0 control of dark squares.}) 14. Rxa6 $1 Rxa6 15. Nxb5 cxb3 16. c4 $1 $16 {[%csl Ge6,Gf5] And Shevchenko regretted putting the pawn on f5 to begin with :)} Bb8 17. cxd5 exd5 18. Bxf6 Rxf6 19. Nc3 O-O 20. Nxd5 Rh6 21. Qxb3 Kh8 22. g3 $18 {1-0 (60) Nabaty,T (2638)-Shevchenko,K (2633) Struga 2021}) 11. Na2 c3 12. a5 $1 $14 {This is a line I recommend in my 1. d4 course on Chessable. I feel black position is too unstable and rigid as the knight shifts to d3 and eventually white might gain space on the kingside while the Queenside for black looks shaky to say the least.} h6 13. Bf4 g5 14. Ne5 $1 {Might be very strong and doesn't allow us to enter the main idea. I mean, I showcase all this subtleties here because I have quite a lot of experience, but it is not likely you ever would reach this level of precision in 99% of the games. But who knows! Theory evolves quickly!}) 9. Bf4 g5 10. Bg3 b5 $5 {This might be a decent try considering the current theory, as the same approach for white doesn't work that well. Here 10. ... Nh5 runs into 11. Ne2! as c5-c4 doesn't exist with b3 beeing played.} 11. a4 c4 12. Be2 b4 13. Na2 c3 14. a5 Be7 $132 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gf6e4] Ne4 will be coming and our c8 bishop will likely shift through e8.}) 7... Nxc5 $11 {White would be happy to do this exchange with the knight on c6, as Ne2-c4 would still follow. Definetely check 1-0 (67) Alonso Rosell,A (2502)-Llanes Hurtado,M (2483) Don Benito 2012 to see how unpleasant it can be.} 8. Bb5+ Bd7 9. Bxd7+ Ncxd7 10. Nd4 Qb6 $15 {10. ... Kf7 was even a better solution but black is perfect. c4 is not happening any time soon and we have good control of light and dark squares.} 11. O-O Be7 12. Nce2 g6 13. c4 e5 14. Nb5 dxc4 15. Qa4 Qc6 16. Bxf6 Bxf6 17. Qxc4 Qxc4 18. Nd6+ Ke7 19. Nxc4 Rhc8 20. Rac1 Rc6 21. Na5 Rxc1 22. Rxc1 b6 23. Nb3 Kd6 24. Nc3 a6 25. e4 Bg5 26. Rd1+ Ke6 27. g3 Rc8 28. Kg2 Rc4 29. h4 Bh6 30. exf5+ gxf5 31. Kf1 b5 32. Na5 Rc7 33. Kg2 b4 34. Nd5 Rc5 35. Nb7 Rxd5 36. Nd8+ Kd6 37. Nf7+ Kc6 38. Rc1+ Bxc1 39. Nh6 {0-1 (39) Cuenca Jimenez,J (2552)-Alonso Rosell,A (2570) Warsaw 2021} *

