1. d4 f5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bg5 d5 4. Bxf6 exf6 {The combination of f6-f5 reduces a lot our flexibility and doing typical maneouvres like Nc6-Ne7-Nc8-Nd6 to make good use of the e4 square, might be less achievable as the f8 bishop would also love the d6 square. We need to take into account that we have more space in general but it is a hard puzzle to solve in the first moves. If white doesn't play great we can get a really sound advantage. I played quite often this variation with White and it's one those variations where knowing the precise move order or not is basically life and death.} 5. e3 {[%cal Gf1d3,Gh2h3,Gg2g4] Usually white wants to go for h3-g4 an seize control of the light squares, as if it was a Rossolimo variation.} Be6 6. Bd3 (6. Qf3 $5 g6 $1 {Now 7. Nce2 is less appealing so we can directly go for securing the queenside.} 7. Nge2 (7. h3 h5 8. Bd3 Bf7 $132 {[%csl Gf6][%cal Gb8c6,Gd8d7,Gf8g7,Yc6e7,Ye7c8,Yc8d6,Ye8c8] We have everything defended and we might go for Nc6-Qd7 (and maybe Bg7 to defend f6) and later decide whether we want to castle long or look for Ne7-Nc8 manouvres directly.}) 7... c6 8. Nf4 Bf7 $11 {[%cal Gh7h5,Gh8g8,Gb8d7,Gf8d6] We can easily develop h5, Bd6, Nd7 and maybe Rg8 to look for g5 ideas. White doesn't have any significant break and we are more than fine.}) (6. h4 g6 $5 7. Bd3 {7. h5 g5! and thank you very much.} Qd7 {We'll show another great example of manouvering.} 8. Nge2 Nc6 9. Nf4 Bf7 10. a3 Ne7 11. Qf3 c6 12. g3 Nc8 13. Qg2 Nd6 14. f3 O-O-O 15. O-O-O $17 Re8 16. Rhe1 Bh6 17. Kb1 Re7 18. g4 fxg4 19. fxg4 Rhe8 20. g5 Bg7 21. Qf3 f5 22. h5 Qd8 23. Re2 Ne4 24. Bxe4 dxe4 25. Qg3 Rd7 26. hxg6 hxg6 27. Red2 b6 28. Nfe2 Kb7 29. Nf4 Rh8 30. Qg2 Rh4 31. d5 cxd5 32. Ncxd5 Rg4 33. Qe2 a6 34. Nb4 Rxd2 35. Rxd2 Rg1+ 36. Rd1 Qxd1+ {0-1 (36) Buksa,N (2410)-Vallejo Pons,F (2694) chess24.com INT 2019}) (6. Bb5+ $5 {Since we rely often in playing Nc6 this move can be annoying. I even play it many many years ago.} c6 7. Bd3 Nd7 8. Qf3 {[%csl Rf5][%cal Rh2h3,Rg2g4] The idea is to go for h3-g4 now but it doesn't really work if we dig a bit.} g6 9. h3 {It had good score as playing 9. ... h5 looks scary.} h5 $1 (9... Bb4 {Now 10. g4 would've gave me a pleasant edge. ½-½ (29) Alonso Rosell,A (2493)-Narciso Dublan,M (2532) Sabadell 2011}) 10. g4 hxg4 11. hxg4 fxg4 12. Bxg6+ Ke7 $1 13. Qg2 Bh6 {[%cal Gf6f5] We threat f5} 14. Bd3 f5 $15 {[%cal Gd7f6,Gd8d6,Ye7d7,Yd7c7] Suddenly Nf6 and Qd6 and our position is insanely good.}) 6... Qd7 7. Nge2 (7. Qf3 Nc6 8. a3 O-O-O {[%cal Gc6e5]} 9. Nge2 g5 $1 {[%csl Re2,Rf3] I remember facing a structure like this. Suddenly white is paralyzed and we'll admire how Cheparinov improves the c6 knight without counter.} 10. g3 Kb8 11. O-O-O Ne7 12. h4 Bg7 13. Kb1 Nc8 14. Qg2 Qf7 15. f3 h6 16. Nc1 Nd6 17. Nb3 Rhe8 {After achieving full control, now black switches to the queenside.} 18. Rhe1 c6 $15 19. a4 Qc7 20. Nc5 Bc8 21. Qf2 Re7 22. Bf1 Rde8 23. b3 Bf8 24. Kb2 Qb6 25. Ra1 a5 26. Ka2 h5 27. Rad1 Bh6 28. f4 g4 29. Qd2 Bf8 30. Rb1 Ka8 31. Bg2 Qa7 32. Ka1 b6 33. Nd3 Re6 34. Nd1 Qe7 35. Rb2 Bb7 36. Kb1 Ba6 37. c3 Qc7 38. N1f2 Kb8 39. Rc2 Qe7 40. Nd1 Ka7 41. N3f2 Rb8 42. Ra2 Rd8 43. Nb2 Re8 44. Nbd1 Bb7 45. Bf1 Rd8 46. Rb2 Qe8 47. Qc2 c5 48. Bd3 cxd4 49. cxd4 Rc8 50. Qe2 Re7 51. Rc2 Rec7 52. Rxc7 Rxc7 53. Nb2 Rc3 54. Ka2 Ne4 55. Nxe4 fxe4 56. Bb5 Qe7 57. Kb1 Rxb3 58. Rc1 Qa3 59. Rc7 Bd6 60. Rd7 Rxe3 61. Qc2 Rc3 62. Qe2 Rc7 {0-1 (62) Lin,Y (2360)-Cheparinov,I (2702) China 2018}) 7... Nc6 {[%cal Gc6b4]} 8. a3 {Since our kingside will always be somewhat weak, White's best approach is to go for a queenside expansion.} g5 $5 {An usual move at this point, we prevent Nf4.} 9. Na4 {[%cal Ga4c5]} (9. f4 O-O-O $132 {[%cal Gc8b8,Gc6e7,Ge7c8,Gc8d6]}) 9... b6 10. b3 {[%cal Rc2c4]} Na5 {White wants to go for c2-c4!} 11. Ba6 $5 $146 (11. Nb2 O-O-O $1 {Would've been a more precise move. The long castle is pretty solid and we always have f5-f4 as a resource.} (11... Bd6 12. c4 dxc4 13. Nxc4 Nxc4 14. Bxc4 Bxc4 15. bxc4 Qc6 $5 {Would've been required, as I found myself into a very bad pawnstructure.} (15... c5 16. Qd3 Qe6 17. O-O O-O 18. Nc3 Rad8 19. a4 f4 20. Nd5 fxe3 21. fxe3 f5 22. Rf3 cxd4 23. exd4 f4 24. Rff1 Rde8 25. Qc3 Rc8 26. Qb3 Kg7 27. Rae1 Qf5 28. a5 Rb8 29. axb6 axb6 30. Qb2 $132 {1-0 (57) Mitrabha,G  (2509)-Alonso Rosell,A (2570) Warsaw 2021})) 12. c4 dxc4 13. bxc4 (13. Nxc4 Nc6 $132 {[%cal Gc8b8,Gh7h5,Gh5h4,Gh4h3] Again White attack stopped abrubtly, we could go for Kb8 and push the h pawn or the f pawn aswell.}) 13... Kb8 {[%cal Gf5f4] f4 is coming and our bishops are loving it.}) 11... Bd6 $132 {[%cal Ge8g8,Ga8e8] Okay then. We castle short and Rae8 and look for f5-f4 looks very coordinated.} *

