{[%evp 0,77,12,27,83,76,69,69,65,62,67,49,66,61,70,54,35,25,5,5,-7,-10,-1,0,0,-19,-4,-23,-13,-50,-45,-74,-43,-37,-28,-52,-67,-73,-81,-75,-38,-40,0,-21,-15,-21,0,-36,-23,-27,-26,-25,-8,-12,-14,-21,-14,-37,-28,-20,-38,-35,-43,-41,-47,-52,-47,-37,-38,0,0,0,-13,-13,-22,-34,-20,-1018,-1018,-1523]} 1. d4 f5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. Bf4 {This is a creative combination of ideas. 3. ... g6 is very bad as 4.h4 here almost wins so it is possible you'll see it in a game. It is also recommended in the Jobava-London Course from Hans Niemann.} (3. e4 fxe4 {Transponses}) (3. Nf3 e6 {[%cal Gf8b4]} 4. a3 $5 d5 {[%cal Gc7c5,Ga7a6,Gb8d7] Followed by c5-a6 looks logical.}) 3... e6 4. g4 $5 {White has this specific idea appart from the topics we talked about the London approach.} (4. e3 Bb4 $1 {[%cal Gb4e1] As in the main line with 2.c4 and 3.Nc3 we love to get the Dutch "Nimzo'd".} 5. Nge2 (5. Bd3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 Nc6 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Gd7d6,Ge6e5] d6-e5 will be coming and the c3 pawn is awful. White was 2 bishops but the positions remains closed. We could secure the queenside later on with Qe7-Bd7-b6 and we'll be on the drivers seat!}) 5... d5 {[%csl Rc3,Re2][%cal Gb4d6,Re2f3,Rc3d2] We'll return to d6 and we have an amazing Stonewall as both white knights are on the wrong squares.}) 4... fxg4 5. h3 g3 {[%cal Gd7d5,Gc7c5] I think this is the easiest way to play against it. We'll look for d5-c5-Nc6 next and our development is pretty smooth. Usually g4 players want blood and we'll give them a positional and easy position for us.} 6. Bxg3 d5 7. Qd3 c5 8. Nf3 Nc6 (8... c4 $5 9. Qe3 Bb4 $14 {[%cal Gh1g1,Gh3h4] It is very hard to understand but in general I don't like to fix the pawn structure with white having clear dominance on the center. You might fancy this position if you are a Winawer player.}) 9. a3 {[%cal Gc3b5] Was Niemann suggestion to threaten Nb5.} (9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. O-O-O O-O $132 {[%cal Gf6h5] I'd say this position is crazy enough. Nh5 ideas and also Qe7-Rd8 and then Bd7-Be8 would be a very interesting approach.}) 9... Bd6 10. dxc5 Bxg3 11. fxg3 e5 12. O-O-O e4 13. Qe3 Qe7 $132 {[%cal Ge7c5] And we'll get back the c5 pawn.} *

