1. d4 f5 2. c4 e6 {I'd say the clasical approach excels to counter this agressive setup.} 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. e3 {I choose this setup with plenty of success in the past, even with a win against my first coach and a famous Dutch player Viktor Moskalenko!} (4. a3 {White prevents us from Nimzoing, so we quickly readjust the approach.} g6 $1 5. h4 (5. Bf4 Bg7 6. e3 O-O 7. Nf3 d6 8. Be2 Nc6 $132 {[%cal Gd8e7,Gc6d8,Gd8f7] And we have a similar position covered in the London-ish approach to the Dutch, but with the extra a2-a3 played. Qe7-Nd8-Nf7 was the chosen plan.}) (5. Nf3 Bg7 6. g3 d6 7. Bg2 O-O 8. O-O Ne4 $132 {e7-e6 is far more useful than a2-a3. We'll end up playing Nxc3 and e5 and we get an excellent Leningrad.}) (5. e3 $5 {White can readjust now that we go for the Leningrad approach. Be2-b4-Bb2 is definetely a dangerous setup, still to be discovered.} b6 $5 {We create some concrete threats to annoy our opponent.} 6. Be2 Bb7 {[%csl Rg2]} 7. Bf3 d5 {[%cal Gc7c6,Gd8d7,Gf8d6] We have a very interesting Stonewall where White might have some troubles readjusting his pieces.}) 5... d6 {We prevent h4-h5 calmly.} (5... Bg7 6. h5 Nxh5 7. e4 $16 {[%cal Gh1h5]} Nf6 8. e5 $1 $18 {That's why 5. ... d6 is useful.}) 6. e3 Bg7 {We do a final "bait" for h4-h5.} 7. Be2 h6 $132 {[%csl Gg4][%cal Ge6e5] We'll end up playing e5 eventually and we have the g4 square for the knight in the future.}) (4. Nf3 Bb4 5. Bd2 {There is a bias in the results, as most games from this position turn out to be from weaker players on the White side. Having said that, I think it is not that stupid for white to play like this.} (5. Qb3 c5 {Feels easier.} 6. a3 (6. e3 {Rarely played but very good.} Nc6 (6... Ne4 7. Bd2 Nxd2 8. Nxd2 b6 $132 {[%cal Gc8b7] Also feels easy to play.}) 7. a3 Bxc3+ 8. Qxc3 Ne4 9. Qd3 O-O {[%cal Gb7b6,Ga7a5,Ga5a4] We can keep up with b6-a5-a4 or even a5-a4 to annoy on the light squares and not let White to get comfortable.}) (6. dxc5 Na6 7. a3 Bxc3+ 8. Qxc3 Nxc5 $132 {[%cal Gc5e4,Gb7b6,Yd7d6,Ye6e5] Black is doing great as if it was a Nimzo. Nce4 and looking for d6-e5 or b6-Bb7-Rc8 should be excellent.}) (6. Bg5 Nc6 7. e3 h6 $11 {[%csl Rf3] White wishes he had the knight on e2.}) 6... Ba5 $1 7. dxc5 Na6 $132 {[%cal Ga6c5,Gc5e4,Gb7b6,Gc8b7,Ya8c8]}) 5... O-O 6. e3 b6 {You have plenty of examples to play this setups.} 7. Bd3 Bxc3 {I prefer to change inmediately the course of action. We'll see why.} (7... Bb7 8. O-O d6 9. a3 Bxc3 10. Bxc3 Ne4 11. Be1 $1 Nd7 12. Nd2 Qg5 13. f4 $1 {To avoid enpassant later on.} Qg6 14. Nxe4 Bxe4 15. Bxe4 fxe4 16. Qa4 Nf6 $16 {A couple games reached until here and now 17.h3!? to prevent Ng4 followed by b4-Rc1-Rf2 and c5 ideas should be great. 1-0 (68) Lokander,M (2475)-Arnaudov,P (2469) Germany 2022 0-1 (62) Petkov,M  (2315)-Amin,B (2686) Chess.com INT 2020 : 0-1 (62) Petkov,M (2315)-Amin,B  (2686) Chess.com INT 2020}) 8. Bxc3 Ne4 $5 $132 {[%cal Ge4c3,Gc8b7] Before White can castle and sneak Bc3-Be1!}) (4. Bg5 Bb4 {[%cal Gc7c5] White is nowhere near to challenge the center and we have a very reasonable version of the Nimzo.} 5. Qb3 (5. e3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 h6 $15 {[%csl Rc3,Rc4][%cal Gd7d6,Ge6e5] Later on we'll go for d6-e5 and I already prefer black.}) (5. Qc2 c5 $5 {This move works better as d4 needs to be attended. Again we can appreciate the similarities with the Nimzo Qc2. Since d7-d5 ideas are less appealing with f7-f5 played, we look for this break.} 6. e3 h6 7. Bxf6 Qxf6 8. Nge2 cxd4 9. Nxd4 Nc6 $132 {Black is doing perfectly fine.}) (5. Rc1 O-O 6. e3 h6 7. Bxf6 Qxf6 $132 {[%cal Gd7d6,Ge6e5,Gc7c6] We can even go for c6!? (to cover the d5 square and maybe even hide the bishop on e7), d6, e5 and we are doing fine with the bishop pair.}) 5... c5 (5... a5 {Many years ago I experienced how this setup also works very well if White is not prepared. I prefer 5. ... c5 over 5. ... a5 as here 6. e3-Nge2 plan is very annoying.} 6. Nf3 O-O 7. e3 h6 8. Bxf6 Qxf6 9. Be2 $11 {[%cal Gb7b6] 1/2-1/2 (56) Alonso Rosell,A (2196) -Fernandez Aguado,E (2361) Barcelona 2006}) 6. e3 (6. a3 Bxc3+ 7. Qxc3 cxd4 8. Qxd4 Nc6 9. Qc3 h6 $15 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Yb7b6,Yc8b7] That would be a great example on how it can go very wrong for white. Now b6-Bb7-Rc8 is coming and White was in trouble in ½-½ (30) Melin,P (2061)-Hauser,J (2086) ICCF email 2005}) 6... Nc6 $132 {[%cal Gc6a5,Gh7h6] We want to keep up with h7-h6 and 7. Nge2 is risky due to the extra option Na5! winning a pawn.}) (4. Qc2 $5 {This prophylaxis has some venom. Again I even play it with White many years ago. If we try to play 4. ... d7-d5, white has an excellent Stonewall with Bf4. If we go for 4. ... Bb4 5. a3 getting the bishop pair and playing something like e3-Nh3-b4-Bb2-f3 (to control e4 square) looks incredibly unpleasant and I feel some PTSD from Lc0-Stockfish match. The latter plan is not that common but feels so unpleasant and simple that I refuse to ignore it.} b6 $5 {Now we shift to this pseudo-Queensindian. Since White commited to Qc2, makes a bit more sense to play around.} 5. e3 $5 {The most common answer once White forced us to play b7-b6.} (5. a3 Bb7 6. Bg5 Be7 $132 {[%cal Gf6e4] We love to go for Ne4 if we can.}) 5... Bb7 6. a3 {The key prophylactic move as our blacksquared bishop can be a bit stupid sometimes. We have a young Wojtaszek winning with it for example.} (6. Nf3 Ne4 $5 {Bb4 is playable but I don't like this kind of Nimzo positions. This way we can exchange 4 pieces or keep the f8 bishop.} (6... Bb4 7. a3 Bxc3+ 8. Qxc3 a5 9. b3 O-O 10. Bb2 d6 11. Be2 Nbd7 12. O-O Qe7 $14 {[%cal Gc3c2,Gf3d2,Gf3e1] And now White would go for the typical Qc2 and eventual Ne1 or Nd2 and welp we don't really want to open the position against 2 bishops. But if you like this kind of stuff feel free.}) 7. a3 {Otherwise Bb4 was the idea.} Nxc3 8. Qxc3 Be7 {[%cal Gd7d6,Ga7a5,Ge8g8] And he have a very well timed random correspondance game to prove my point. Feels so good. 0-1 (53) Blake,M (2199)-Koval,V (2124) ICCF email 2016}) (6. f3 c5 {[%cal Gb8c6]} 7. d5 Na6 8. e4 Bd6 $132) 6... c5 {I like it more than Bd6 but it's a matter of styles.} 7. Nf3 (7. d5 {A known thematic sacrifice. Here it works decent as f5 is weak and Be2!?-Bf3 can be a follow up as we saw in 1-0 (41) Kryakvin,D (2523)-Pshmahov,O (2095) Novorossiysk 2022} Na6 {[%cal Ga6c7] We follow up with Nc7 and i'd say our position make sense. Considering long castle is even a possibility.}) 7... Ne4 $5 {[%cal Gf8e7,Ge7f6] We make room for the bishop and our position has easier play. Also Bxf3 might be on the menu later on if White is not careful.}) (4. f3 {[%cal Gd7d5,Gc7c5] Playing f5 in the f3 nimzo is something interesting, so here we have it for free. The easiest plan would be to go for Stonewall and c7-c5 later to pressure the weakened a7-g1 diagonal.} d5 5. Bg5 Be7 6. e3 O-O 7. Bd3 c5 {[%cal Gb8c6] Black was more than fine in 1-0 (50) Ivanisevic,I (2662)-Rombaldoni,A (2518) Bergamo 2015}) (4. Bf4 {This move is pretty bad now. We have a perfect excuse to play Bb4.} Bb4 5. e3 (5. Qc2 Bxc3+ $5 {I mean d6 was fine but we have a sweet trick making use of the bishop en f4.} 6. Qxc3 Ne4 7. Qc2 (7. Qa3 d6 {[%cal Ge6e5,Gd8f6,Yd8d2] And now e6-e5 is a threat and Qf6 can be a nail in the coffin.}) 7... c5 {[%cal Gd8a5] We can take everything on d2 and after Na6 we have an excellent endgame}) 5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 b6 $15 {[%cal Gd7d6,Yb8c6,Yc6a5,Yc8a6,Gc8b7,Gb8d7] Black has an amazing Nimzoesque position. ½-½ (44) Kveinys,A (2518)-Vallejo Pons,F (2711) Tallinn 2016}) 4... d5 $5 {I prefer to switch to the stonewall. White usually wants Bd3-Nge2-f3 and eventually go for e3-e4.} (4... Bb4 $14 {This kind of setups are less appealing as White can go for Bd2-Bd3-Nge2 with ease and have full control of the e4 square.}) 5. Bd3 c6 6. Nge2 {The most common plan.} (6. Nf3 {White can shift to a classical approach, seen pretty often with black to face Zukerkot players that want to push f2-f4. Can be tricky to face of b3-Bb2-Ne2-Ne5-f3.} Bd6 7. O-O Ne4 {As usual we want to take action before castling.} (7... O-O 8. Ne2) 8. Ne2 (8. Ne5 O-O 9. f3 (9. f4 Nd7 10. Nxe4 fxe4 11. Be2 Nxe5 12. fxe5 Rxf1+ 13. Bxf1 Be7 $11 {0-1 (53) Yang,K (2481)-Bachmann,A (2588) Chess.com INT 2022}) 9... Nc5 $5 $146 {A creative resource.} 10. Be2 Bxe5 11. dxe5 dxc4 $132 {[%csl Rc1,Re5][%cal Gb7b5,Gb5b4] We'll play b5-b4 and Whites bishops are very passive to be a threat.}) 8... Nd7 9. b3 g5 $5 {[%csl Ge5,Gf4][%cal Gd8f6] We control the dark squares very well.} 10. Bb2 Qf6 {[%csl Ge5]} 11. Qc1 (11. a4 a5 (11... g4 $5 $16 {This is definetely very risky.} 12. Ne1 Qh6 13. Nf4 Ndf6 {The queen on d1 is better than in c1 (11.Qc1), as it covers f3 in case of Ng5-Rg8 plans.} 14. Be2 Rg8 15. Ned3 Ng5 16. Ba3 Bc7 17. Ne5 $16 {Tecnically white is a bit better here but some claim could be made to be interesting enough for black!?}) 12. Ba3 Bxa3 13. Rxa3 b6 $132 {[%cal Gc8b7,Ge8g8] White did exchange our bishop pair but we managed to keep the control of the dark squares.}) 11... g4 (11... a5 12. a4 Rg8 $5 13. Ba3 Bc7 $132 {[%cal Gf6h6] Is another way to annoy White.}) 12. Ne1 (12. Nd2 {Even black won in correspondence here!} Qh6 13. Nf4 Ndf6 14. Nxe4 fxe4 15. Be2 Nh5 16. Bxg4 Nxf4 17. exf4 Rg8 18. Qd1 Qxf4 19. Bh5+ Ke7 20. g3 Qf5 21. Bc1 Bd7 22. Be3 Raf8 23. Kh1 Kd8 24. Rg1 Kc8 25. Rb1 Kb8 26. Be2 h5 27. Bxh5 e5 28. cxd5 cxd5 29. Be2 Qh7 30. dxe5 Bxe5 31. Rg2 Qf7 32. Bh5 Qe6 33. Rc1 Bc6 34. Bc5 Rc8 35. Be2 Rc7 36. f4 exf3 37. Bxf3 Rf7 38. Rcc2 Rxf3 39. Qxf3 d4 40. Qe2 Rd8 41. Bb4 Bd5 42. Rd2 Re8 43. Rd1 a5 44. Bd2 d3 45. Qf2 b6 46. Kg1 Qg4 47. Re1 Kb7 48. h3 Qxh3 49. Rh2 Qg4 50. Rh7+ Ka6 51. Rh4 Qg7 52. Re3 Bd6 53. Rxd3 Bc5 54. Rdd4 Bb7 55. Be3 Ka7 56. Kf1 Qg6 57. Ke1 Re7 58. Rhg4 Qb1+ 59. Rd1 Qh7 {0-1 (59) Slawinski,T (2405)-Laffranchise,L (2477) ICCF email 2017}) 12... Qh6 13. Nf4 Ndf6 {[%csl Yg1][%cal Ge4g5,Gh8g8,Gd6c7,Yc8d7,Yf6e4]} 14. Be2 Ng5 15. Ned3 Rg8 16. Ba3 Bc7 $132 {[%cal Gc8d7,Gf6e4,Gg5f3] Not fun for White.}) 6... Bd6 7. f3 {White can, according to the engine, castle, but who wants to risk Bxh2+?} (7. Qc2 {This move is played quite often but it is not very precise and we have a better version of our plan.} O-O 8. f3 dxc4 $1 (8... Kh8 $5 {This was the first time I learned about this idea, precisely OTB! Managed to win but felt unpleasant to go for e3-e4 and leave all my dark squares weak.} 9. Bd2 dxc4 10. Bxc4 Qe7 (10... b5 $1 $132 {[%cal Ga7a5]}) 11. Bd3 Nd5 12. a3 Nxc3 13. Bxc3 Nd7 14. O-O Nf6 15. Rae1 Bd7 16. Kh1 Rae8 17. Bd2 Bc8 18. Nc3 Nd5 19. e4 Nxc3 20. Bxc3 Qc7 21. g3 $16 {1-0 (58) Alonso Rosell,A  (2528)-Thejkumar,M (2467) Sitges 2015}) (8... Nbd7 9. Bd2 dxc4 10. Bxc4 Nb6 11. Bb3 Nfd5 12. O-O Kh8 {Was the version of the plan that I faced many years ago, but It doesn't work as well for black.} 13. a3 Bd7 14. e4 Nxc3 15. Bxc3 $16 {[%csl Gb3,Gc3]} c5 16. dxc5 Bxc5+ 17. Kh1 Rc8 18. Rad1 Qc7 19. exf5 Rxf5 20. Ng3 Rg5 21. Ne4 Rg6 22. Nxc5 Qxc5 23. Qd2 Nd5 24. Bd4 Qe7 25. Rfe1 Qh4 26. Re4 Qd8 27. Qe2 a6 28. Bxd5 exd5 29. Re7 Bb5 30. Qe5 Qf8 31. Rxb7 Re8 32. Qxd5 Bc6 33. Rxg7 Qxg7 34. Bxg7+ Kxg7 35. Qd4+ Kg8 36. h4 {1-0 (36) Alonso Rosell,A  (2461)-Moskalenko,V (2558) Figueres 2009}) 9. Bxc4 b5 10. Bb3 Kh8 {[%csl Rc2][%cal Ge6e5] Black is doing an excellent job already.} 11. O-O a5 12. a3 e5 $132 {0-1 (82) Bok,B (2624)-Narayanan,S (2658) Chess.com INT 2022}) 7... O-O 8. O-O dxc4 $1 $132 {This idea appears from time to time in the Stonewall. We want to go for Kh8 and then a5-b5-Na6 and always answer e3-e4 with fxe4 and e5, getting a nice blockade in dark squares.} 9. Bxc4 b5 {Now white has a couple moves.} 10. Bb3 (10. Bd3 Nbd7 $1 {[%cal Ga7a6,Gc6c5] No we can afford to go for a semislav style with a6-c5.} 11. a3 a6 $1 {[%cal Gc6c5]} 12. e4 fxe4 13. Nxe4 Nxe4 14. Bxe4 Qc7 $132 {[%cal Gd7f6,Ge6e5] We have an amazingly interesting position.}) 10... a5 {[%cal Ga5a4,Ge6e5,Yb8a6] Since Nbd7 is not possible, we want to make sure we have Na6 as an option later on so including a7-a5 is great. At the same time we threat a5-a4 to be able to counter e3-e4 with e6-e5.} 11. e4 $5 {White can try to go all-in while we lack some development.} (11. a3 Kh8 {[%cal Ge6e5]} 12. e4 {Let's check some examples of initiative. It kinda feels like the Fantasy variation in the carokhan.} fxe4 13. fxe4 (13. Nxe4 Nxe4 14. fxe4 e5 15. Be3 Nd7 $132 {[%cal Gc8b7]}) (13. Bg5 exf3 14. Rxf3 e5 15. Ne4 Bg4 $132 {[%cal Gd6e7] Not much fireworks for white.}) 13... e5 $15 {[%csl Rb3,Rc3,Re2] White minor pieces are really sad about the pawn structure.}) 11... fxe4 12. Bg5 $5 exf3 13. Rxf3 a4 {Most logical move.} 14. Bc2 Nbd7 {[%cal Gd8e7]} 15. Qd3 Qe7 $132 {[%cal Gb5b4,Gc8a6] We have b5-b4 and Ba6 to free ourselves and I'm happy to end up here. I don't like to put this weird lines but the engine was quite happy inmediately and can be tricky here..} *

