{[%evp 0,24,34,28,69,46,46,46,46,17,26,17,23,21,32,27,32,11,18,0,-8,-4,-4,-9,4,4,28]} 1. d4 f5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 {White can play the orthodox way without playing Nc3 to prevent Bb4.} (3. g3 Nf6 4. Bg2 Bb4+ $5 {I also wanted to briefly mention this option. Is a bit risky but easy to play as d6-e5 would follow. It's very risky as White has a very pleasant position and obviously will push on the queenside (which is the good plan) but can be played from time to time. I'll leave you this classical game where I got an amazing position.} 5. Bd2 Bxd2+ 6. Qxd2 O-O 7. Nc3 d6 8. Nf3 Qe8 9. O-O e5 10. dxe5 dxe5 11. Nd5 Ne4 12. Qa5 Nc6 $1 13. Qa3 Rf7 14. Rfd1 Be6 15. b4 Bxd5 16. cxd5 Nd8 17. b5 Rd7 18. Bh3 g6 19. g4 Rg7 $132 {[%cal Gd8f7,Gf7d6] 1/2-1/2 (66) Peralta,F (2551)-Alonso Rosell,A (2530) Barcelona 2017}) 3... Nf6 4. e3 b6 5. Be2 {5. Bd3 doesn't change much as we will also go for castle and Ne4.} Bb7 6. O-O Be7 7. Nc3 (7. b3 O-O 8. Bb2 Ne4 9. Nfd2 {This position needs to be mentioned as it happened in ½-½ (61) Rapport,R (2747)-Carlsen,M (2882) Saint Louis 2019. Here black mas fine after} d5 10. Nxe4 dxe4 $132 {[%cal Gb8d7,Ge7d6]}) 7... O-O 8. b3 (8. d5 {White often looks for punishing our b7 bishop, but here is less threatening as if White had the bishop on g2 and Nd4 was coming.} Ne4 9. Nd4 Nxc3 10. bxc3 e5 11. Nc2 d6 12. f4 Nd7 13. fxe5 dxe5 14. Bd3 e4 $19 {Gunina is very tricky but the position was hopeless 1-0 (26) Gunina,V (2525)-Charochkina,D (2383) Doha 2016}) 8... Ne4 9. Nxe4 (9. Bb2 d5 $5 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gc7c6,Ye7d6,Yd8f6] This is a great time to switch to the Stonewall. We efficiently did the fianchetto first.}) 9... fxe4 10. Nd2 d5 $132 {[%cal Gb8d7]} 11. f3 Bg5 $5 {Even 11. ... Nc6!? is good, black has weird dynamics in his favour.} 12. f4 Bf6 $132 {[%cal Gb8c6,Gc6e7,Ge7f5] 0-1 (30) Sobek,J (2261)-Drozniak,S (2062) Karvina 2017} *

