{[%evp 0,30,28,24,69,49,49,49,50,48,63,63,64,78,66,71,66,38,41,36,35,29,51,40,40,40,47,41,52,60,51,54,59]} 1. d4 f5 2. g3 {I'll start with this move order. White benefits from getting strong in the dark squares and the g2 bishop is usually left uncontested through the main diagonal. We cannot compare it to the Queens Indian (where black inmediately challenges the diagonal) or the Catalan with black (where black controls the center enough to create counterplay).} e6 {We'll go for the classical set-up. I feel it is a bit underrated and a bit more consistent and safe than the Leningrad approach. Bear in mind this move order for White allows Ag2-Nd2-e4 which is a bit annoying and kinda easy to play but also playable for black. Got a win and an interesting position aswell against Dubov itself for a example.} (2... Nf6 3. Bg2 g6 4. Nd2 d6 (4... Bg7 5. e4 fxe4 6. Nxe4 Nxe4 7. Bxe4 d5 8. Bg2 Nc6 9. Ne2 Bg4 10. c3 Qd6 11. h3 Bf5 12. Nf4 e5 13. Nxd5 O-O-O 14. O-O Be6 15. dxe5 Nxe5 16. Ne3 Qa6 17. Qc2 Kb8 $132 {0-1 (60) Lopez Martinez,J (2542)-Alonso Rosell,A (2552) Barcelona 2020}) 5. e4 Nc6 6. c3 e5 7. Ne2 Bg7 8. Qb3 $132 {1-0 (31) Dubov,D (2720)-Alonso Rosell,A (2570) Warsaw 2021}) 3. Bg2 Nf6 4. Nf3 (4. Nh3 $5 {[%cal Yg2b7] White kinda gets ahead of us playing the Stonewall. In an ideal world White goes for Nd2-Nf3-Nf4-Nd3 to seize the e5 square. From f4 or g5 the option to go for d4-d5 and weakening the e6 square is also on the menu, but less likely. I don't think it's too smart for white (Since Ne1-Nd3 maneouvre from f3 works pretty well), but also defends the f4 square so an eventual faceoff Bd6-Bf4 might come in handy. Even this positive idea has some issues, as black is happy to retreat with Be7 and leave the knight miserable on h3.} d5 {We'll give the same treatment. 4. ... Be7 and looking for d6-c6 and teasing White's knight with e6-e5 threat is also a decent conceptual approach and very practical.} 5. c4 {Against 5. 0-0 you have the extra option to go for 5. ... Nc6 and 6. ... dxc4 but feels like an unnecessary risky version of the catalan with the pawn on f5.} Bd6 6. O-O O-O {Our goal is to play against the h3 knight.} 7. Qc2 (7. b3 $5 c6 {Now the plans with Nc6-b6  (to answer Nc3 with Ne7!)-h6-g5 are less effective as White is always on time to play Nf4-Nd3 and solve the issues. Not investing a tempo on Qc2 is definetely life changing and it's also a good time to shift to more conventional Stone-wall setups.} 8. Ba3 {Since White knows that we'll react to Bf4 with Be7, usually tries to exchange the bishops this way, so our dark squares become a bit weaker.} (8. Bf4 Be7 {[%cal Gh7h6] h6-g5 is coming.}) 8... Bxa3 9. Nxa3 Qe7 {I feel I got it solved. We wish to go for Ne4 whenever White plays Nf4. Why though? Because f3-Nf2 would be a very efficient answer if we hurry up to control the center. This simple idea is combined with Nbd7-b6-a5 and even g5 ideas often later on. On my experience playing this kind of positions, White is left with a very thin margin for advantage and we have some solid general rules that are not punishing at all. The last phrase sums up pretty well the likeness of the Stonewall overall.} 10. Qc1 (10. Nc2 {This move has some smart ideas but too engine-ish to be afraid off. White wants to counter 10. ... Nbd7 with 11. Ne3!? and go for Qc2-Nf4-Nd3 style.} a5 $1 {This simple novelty fits well with all the assumptions. If Nf4 Ne4 is allowed and if Ne3 Bd7!? and looking for Be8 works smoothly. Usually we should be scared for an eventual cxd5 that forces us to play cxd5, but here with Qe7, a5, b3, Ne3 included, we have plenty of presence in the dark squares and white is a bit sloppy, as the e3 knight was just a defensive move.  10. ... dxc4 11. bxc4 e5!? is a bit unconventional but also very senseful as the c6 pawn shuts down all whites pieces and we could enjoy a good knight on c5 and some pressure thanks to the isolated c4 pawn. White trying to keep his d4 pawn with 12. e3 would definetely make our journey easier after 12. ... e4! and we seize control of the light squares.}) 10... Nbd7 {Again we wait.} 11. Nf4 {Against 11. Qb2 or 11. Nb1 we could follow up with b6-Bb7.} Ne4 {[%cal Gb7b6]} (11... b6 $2 12. cxd5 $16 {[%csl Gc6][%cal Gc1c6,Yc6e6,Yc6a8]}) 12. Nb1 Qf6 $5 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Ge6e5,Gd5c4] We need to consider this move order for White as very tricky (always having the c6 square in sight to prevent b7-b6. This move has some interesting ideas, for instance allowing b7-b6 as cxd5 exd5! and the c6 pawn would be defended by the queen. We also pave the road to play dxc4-e5 ideas. e3 or Rd1 are faced with e5! and black is more than fine.} (12... dxc4 {This is also a very creative approach, that can help you in similar positions. But I prefer in general to avoid opening the position and leaving us with the f5 pawn.} 13. Qxc4 (13. bxc4 e5 $132 {[%csl Rb7,Gc5,Rc6,Rg2] Would be great for black.}) 13... Nb6 {[%cal Ge6e5]} 14. Qc2 e5 15. dxe5 Qxe5 16. Nd2 $14 {[%csl Gf5]})) (7. Bf4 Be7 $1 {[%csl Rh3]} 8. Qc2 {8. Nd2 would also be answered with h6-g5.} Nc6 {[%csl Rh3][%cal Gh7h6,Gg7g5] Friendly reminder that 9. cxd5! was an actual threat so Nc6 also defends c7. Again we achieve the same style of position and h6-g5 would be next.}) 7... Nc6 $5 {We deviate from the conventional Dutch.} 8. Rd1 h6 $5 {[%csl Rh3] I'd say it is easier if we always aim for the knight.} 9. b3 g5 10. Nc3 (10. Bb2 g4 $1 11. Nf4 Bxf4 12. gxf4 Rf7 $17 {[%cal Gc6e7,Ge7g6,Gh6h5,Gh5h4] White is almost losing in practice i'd say.}) (10. f4 {Is a "typical" answer to give some space to the knight, but basically makes our plan very straightforward.} g4 11. Nf2 Rf7 $5 $132 {[%cal Gd6f8,Gh6h5,Gf7h7,Gh5h4] After Bf8-Rh7-h5-h4 we'll se an scared opponent. A really smooth transition later on would be Ne7-Ne4-fxe4 and have room on f5 for the knight.}) 10... b6 $5 $132 {[%csl Rh3][%cal Gc6e7,Ge7g6,Gc8d7,Gc8b7] I like to add this rare approach so you get a richer experience in the Dutch. We rely on the Nb4 threat to prevent answer the obvious 11. cxd5 and we'll keep up with Ne7-Bb7 (or Bd7) and we'll follow up with Ng6, getting some more pressure on the kingside. I feel it is very hard for White to understand were to go from here. B6 can be considered just to prevent c4-c5 and go for Ne7, not necessarily to achieve fianchetto.}) 4... Be7 5. O-O (5. c4 {White can try to delay the castle aswell so our evil plans with h5-h4 are worthless.} d5 6. Nbd2 (6. Nc3 c6 {Would eventually tranpose.}) (6. b3 Ne4 7. Bb2 Nd7 {We can always enjoy the pure Stonewall if White takes a lot of time.} 8. Nc3 (8. Nbd2 c6 9. Qc1 (9. O-O h5 $5 {[%cal Gh5h4] Could be scary for white.}) 9... a5 10. Ba3 O-O 11. Bxe7 Qxe7 12. O-O b5 13. cxb5 cxb5 14. Qb2 b4 $15 {Black was doing great. We see how Nbd2 is usually easily punished.} 15. Rac1 Nc3 16. Nb1 Ne4 17. Nbd2 Ba6 18. Nxe4 fxe4 19. Ne5 Nxe5 20. dxe5 Qa7 21. Bh3 Rae8 22. Rc6 d4 23. Rxe6 Kh8 24. Rxe8 Rxe8 25. e6 Qc5 26. Rc1 Qh5 27. Bf1 Qg5 28. Rc6 Bb5 29. Rd6 d3 30. exd3 exd3 31. Bxd3 Bxd3 32. Rxd3 Rxe6 33. Qd2 Qe5 34. Re3 Qa1+ 35. Kg2 {1-0 (35) Moroni,L (2575)-Rapport,R (2763) Warsaw 2021}) 8... c6) 6... Ne4 $5 7. b3 b6 $5 $146 {[%cal Gc8b7,Ge8g8,Ge7d6,Gd8e7,Gb8d7] This new setup with Bb7-Bd6-Qe7-Nd7 looks a lot like the Zukerkot and takes advantatge of White commiting to Nbd2 and b3.} (7... Nc6 {Rapport played the usual setup to face b3 ideas, but without the early castle from White, it feels a bit empty as h5-h4 is not possible anymore. But we get to an interesting setup that I want to talk about.} 8. Bb2 Bf6 9. e3 O-O 10. O-O a5 11. a3 Bd7 {[%cal Gd7e8,Ge8h5] Didn't even know Rapport did that plan but it is interesting in practice and I got very good results in blitz. We punish players that want to play very schematic, activating the bishop through e8-h5.} 12. Ne5 $1 {I got punished} (12. Qc2 Be8 13. Bc3 Bg6 14. Qb2 Qe7 $132 {1/2-1/2 (40) Gelfand,B (2676)-Rapport,R (2736) Hengshui 2019}) 12... Be8 13. Nd3 Bh5 {A bluff that worked :).} 14. Qxh5 Nxd2 15. Qd1 (15. cxd5 $18) 15... Nxf1 16. Qxf1 Ne7 17. Rc1 c6 $17 {1/2-1/2 (38) Fressinet,L (2633)-Alonso Rosell,A (2548) chess24.com INT 2019})) (5. b3 Ne4 6. Bb2 d5) 5... Ne4 {5. ... d5 is obviously fine aswell and Rapport showed the playability in many ocasions. But here White has the extra options 6. Nfd2, 6. Ne5 and 6. d5!?. You can go straight for 5. ... d5 if you don't want to tease your opponent, but I like to allow options so my opponent can feel "smart" or "tricky" and then strike back. This might help you appreciate how the Dutch often works and maybe you see more ways to play in the future! I feel the old approach (5. ... 0-0 6. c4 d6) is unplayable. I recommend in my chessable course for white 7. Qc2! and black will just be worse.} (5... d5 {I would recommend this move order for begginers as it is more consistent and we need less information.} 6. Ne5 $5 {White might feel smart but the kingside might be unattended.} (6. Nbd2 {Maybe the only significant extra option for White. We face it in a similar way than 6. ... b3} Nc6 $5 {[%csl Rd2][%cal Ga7a5,Ga5a4] And here we can choose to play a5-a4, which is a very typical approach whenever a knight goes to d2 or b3, or even Ne4 and there h5-h4 or just Bf6 controlling the center.}) 6... Nbd7 7. Nd3 h5 $1 {[%cal Gh5h4] And we will have plenty of fun for sure!}) 6. c4 (6. Nfd2 $5 d5 7. Nxe4 dxe4 {[%cal Gc7c5]} 8. Be3 $5 {An interesting idea to get ahead of c7-c5.} (8. f3 exf3 9. exf3 (9. Bxf3 O-O $15 {[%cal Gb8c6,Ge6e5] Followed by Nc6 and e5. 9. ... c5? was wrong due to 10. d5! getting all the white squares 1-0 (22) Strebkovs,A (2356)-Chetverik,M (2260) Trebic 2014}) 9... c5 $1 $132 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Ge7f6] Black is fine.}) 8... Nc6 9. f3 exf3 {Bxf3 will be answered in the same style as in 8. f3} 10. exf3 f4 $5 11. Bf2 h5 $5 {[%cal Gf4g3,Gh5h4]} 12. gxf4 O-O $132 {[%csl Gf4][%cal Ge7d6] We have a nice crazy position.}) (6. Ne5 $5 O-O $5 7. Nd2 (7. c4 d6 {7. ... d5 is obviously fine and likely to transpose to the main line.} 8. Nd3 Nc6 $5 9. d5 {[%csl Ge6] White wants to look for the e6 square.} (9. Be3 Nf6 $5 $132 {[%cal Ge6e5] e6-e5 is coming and White pieces don't make much sense.}) 9... exd5 10. cxd5 Ne5 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Ga7a5]} 11. Nf4 g5 {A reaction is needed as Nd2 was coming and White would exchange one of our best pieces for free.} 12. Nh3 Bf6 13. f4 Ng6 $132 {I'd say this position is complex enough to claim it playable. Friendly reminder that this is not necessary as 5. ... d5 is safe.}) 7... d6 8. Nd3 (8. Nxe4 $5 dxe5 9. Nc5 {[%cal Gc5b7]} e4 {[%cal Ge6e5]} 10. Nb3 a5 11. a4 b6 12. f3 Bb7 $132 {Another example where white can get unpleasant positions very quickly.}) 8... d5 {[%cal Ga7a5,Ga5a4,Gb8c6] And we'll keep up with a5-a4, as usual against the knight on d2.}) (6. b3 d5 {[%cal Gb8c6,Ge7f6,Gh7h5] And we'll keep up with Nc6-h5 ideas.}) (6. d5 $5 {White wants to switch to Leningrad approach.} exd5 7. Qxd5 d6 $132 {[%cal Gc7c6,Ga7a5,Gb8d7,Yd7c5] After c6 we'll go for Nd7-a5-Nc5 and enjoy a decent control of the center. Our pieces have very clear squares to go and we have a very reasonable leningrad-style position.}) 6... d5 {We enter now the critical position. We have a Stonewall set-up and we prefer to delay the castle so we have more flexibility. Props to Rapport for making this position playable on his own.} 7. Nc3 (7. b3 Nc6 $1 {[%cal Gh7h5] The oldest game appears to be from Kortschnoj! But was recenlty brought back into action by Rapport entirely. We play around the idea of delaying castle and going for h5-h4. It has some similarities to the Jobava London since the pawn on f5 has a similar job and White lost some flexibility going for b2-b3.} 8. Bb2 (8. Ba3 Bf6 {[%cal Gh7h5] And h5-h4 is coming.}) 8... h5 $132 {[%cal Gh5h4] We are coming. Definetely feels unpleasant to face this kind of attack and Rapport got some good wins with it alredy.} 9. Nbd2 h4 10. e3 hxg3 11. hxg3 {Was already terrible for White in 0-1 (55) Moroni,L (2575)-Rapport,R (2763) Warsaw 2021} Bd6 $1 $19 {[%cal Gd8f6,Gf6h6] And the queen is coming.}) (7. Ne5 $5 {Let's try to get creative!} Nd7 8. Bf4 {After writing this idea I found that it is actually the recommendation in the great Chessable course Keep It Simple: 1. d4 by Christof Sielecki. Always follow the engine to keep it simple :) jokes aside White wants to prevent us from doing some shenanigans with h5-h4 and a reaction is needed.} (8. Be3 $5 {I want to get a bit ahead of what White can try out of desperation against this solid setup.} c6 {We keep ourselves on the ground.} (8... Nxe5 $6 {Let me show you white's evil intentions.} 9. dxe5 {[%cal Ye3a7,Yg2b7]} c6 10. Qc1 {[%csl Re4] This funny idea can definetely caught you of guard. Suddenly the knight can be in trouble!} d4 11. Rd1 c5 12. f3 Ng5 13. Bf2 Bd7 14. b4 b6 15. b5 $14 {[%cal Ge2e3] e2-e3 is coming and suffering for 40-50 moves aswell.}) 9. Qc2 O-O 10. Nd3 (10. Rd1 Bf6 11. f4 Be7 $132 {[%cal Gd8e8,Ge8h5] We look forward to play Qe8-Qh5 and we get ahead of some expansion on the queenside. We also have the extra option to play Ndf6 or even Nxe5 without losing a pawn.}) 10... Bf6 11. Rd1 b5 $5 {[%cal Gd7b6,Gb6c4] 11. ... g5 or 11. ... a5 are logical for different reasons but I loved this weird concept. We want to head to c4 with the knight and create some havoc. Basically we would have our 3 minor pieces controling dark squares and the pawnchain controling the light ones, so some degree of coordination is implied.} 12. cxb5 cxb5 13. Nc3 Nb6 {[%cal Gc8d7]} 14. b3 {[%csl Rb6] Taking the pawn could be a bit too much as 14. ... Nc4! followed by Bd7 would give us plenty of initiative.} Bd7 $132 {[%cal Gd8e7,Gf8c8,Ga7a5] We want to keep up with our presence in dark squares, so moves like Qe7 or a5 and Rfc8 are welcome.}) (8. Nxd7 Bxd7 9. cxd5 (9. Qb3 Bc6 $11 {[%csl Gd5] Now this move looks more appealing and black is superfine.}) 9... exd5 10. Qb3 Bc8 $132 {The Rapport family (wife and husband) both played Bc6 and got good results, but I see no issues with keeping the pawn structure safe.} 11. f3 {The only serious threat and white tries to delay our castle.} Nf6 12. Nc3 c6 13. e4 dxe4 14. Be3 (14. Qc4 $5 Qd6 $5 {[%cal Gc8e6] And we'll castle.}) 14... Qb6 15. Qc4 Nd5 $1 $132 {[%cal Gc8e6] And we'll castle.}) 8... g5 $5 {Looks like a risky but logical choice. We have this extra option to spicy it up a bit.} (8... c6 {Would basically transpose to the mainline after.} 9. Nd2 O-O 10. Nxe4 {Transposes}) 9. Be3 O-O 10. Qc2 (10. Nc3 Nxe5 11. dxe5 Nxc3 12. bxc3 f4 {[%cal Gc7c6,Gg8h8] Important not to let white to play f2-f4 and then proceed to bash the center with cxd5 and c3-c4 having both bishops pointing to our queenside. Now we'll just go for c6- Kh8 and adjust our bishops.}) 10... Nxe5 11. dxe5 d4 $5 12. Rd1 (12. Bc1 Bd7 $5 {[%cal Gd7c6,Gd8e8,Ya7f2] We don't even care much about the d4 pawn. Playing Bc6-Qe8 and looking to mess with White might be fun!}) 12... c5 $132 {[%cal Gd8c7] I hope you are not in a very close friendship with the e4 knight. After Qc7 we might need to sacrifice it and get advantage of our intimidating pawn structure.}) 7... c6 {Well you could also go for 7. ... Nc6 and 8. ... h5 but i'm not responsible for your losses. White did not commit to b2-b3, Bb2 so it has definetely more presence in the center and easier time countering our fancy attack. Something like 7. ... Nc6 8. Qc2 h5 9. h4 g5 10. hxg5 and black is completely lost.} 8. Ne5 {White wants to create some imbalance and even reroute the knight to d3. Nxe4 followed by f2-f3 is the main concern.} (8. Qc2 {This plan is very standard. White defends the c3 knight and looks for Rb1-b4 or just Bf4 and keep developing.} Nd7 {We keep our options flexible before castling.} 9. Rb1 (9. Bf4 g5 {9. ... 0-0 is definetely playable but I don't want to repeat myself and I want to give you some more structures and ideas.} 10. Be3 {10. Bc1 might be too much and even 10. ... h5!? now can be interesting.} (10. Be5 O-O $132 {[%cal Gg5g4,Gd7e5] And g4 is coming}) 10... O-O (10... h5 $6 {The thing here is that any "panic button" pressed by White is still good for White. When playing the Dutch try to be a bit smart about "complicating" not going all-in all the time is important. Again we are not even threatening that much after h5-h4 as White has all the presence in the center.} 11. Ne5 $16 {[%csl Ya8,Yc8,Yh8] Might be the easiest move and we will definetely pay for not having both sides coordinated.}) 11. Nxe4 (11. Qc1 {[%csl Rg5]} h6 12. h4 {The engine usually looks for this kind of inhuman plans but I feel it very hard to believe.} gxh4 13. Bxh6 Rf7 $13 {[%cal Gf7h7] If White fancies this kind of position we'll definetely let them.}) (11. Rad1 {Getting pieces to the center looks more dangerous than it looks. Friendly reminder that we are lacking 2 pieces into the action, so Nf3-Ne5 ideas are scary. On a more general basis, whenever we do a flank attack we need to be extremely careful about the center not beeing open!. I would definetely prepare this with white as now the "obvious move" 11. ... Bf6 would be facing 12. Qc1! h6 13. h4!. Funny how this Rad1-Qc1 appears to be interesting for white quite often against the Stonewall.} Nd6 12. b3 {12. c5 Nf7 and keep up with b6-Bb7 would be fine for black. I mean, White put everything into the center and now pushes into the queenside?.} Nf7 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gb7b6] Looks like the healthiest option and later on look for b6 or Rb8-b5 even.} (12... b6 $132 {This was played in a game between the best Correspondence players. Again it requires very precise play for White to take advantage through all the board.} 13. Qc1 $1 {[%csl Gg5]} Nf7 14. b4 $1 b5 15. cxb5 cxb5 16. Nxb5 Nb6 17. Ne5 Ba6 $132 {[%csl Re3,Rg2] Black got a very "human" compensation for just a pawn as we enjoy the a6-f1 diagonal, the c4 square, and both bishops for white are a bit sad.} 18. Nc6 Qd7 19. Nxe7+ Qxe7 20. Nc3 Bc8 21. Qb1 Bd7 22. Rd3 a6 23. Bc1 Rac8 24. b5 axb5 25. Nxb5 Bxb5 26. Qxb5 Nc4 27. Qb1 Nfd6 28. Rb3 Kg7 29. Rd1 Rc7 30. Bf3 Na5 31. Rb4 Nac4 32. a3 h6 33. Qb3 Ne4 34. Kg2 Nf6 35. Kg1 Ne4 36. Bxe4 fxe4 37. Rf1 Qf6 38. Qd1 Rcf7 39. Rb3 Kg8 40. Be3 Qg6 41. Kg2 Ra7 42. Bc1 Qf6 43. f3 Raf7 44. a4 Kg7 45. h3 Kg8 46. Rg1 Ra7 47. Rb4 Raf7 48. Rb3 Ra7 49. Rb4 Qg6 50. g4 Raf7 51. Rb3 Ra7 52. Rb4 Qf6 53. Rb5 Qg6 54. Rb4 {1/2-1/2 (54) Kruse,H (2650)-Bernal Varela,N (2614) FICGS email 2018}) (12... Bf6 {Richard suffered quite a lot after} 13. Bc1 $1 {[%cal Gc1a3] The bishop smoothly shifts to a3-f8.} Rf7 14. Ba3 Ne4 15. Nxe4 fxe4 16. Ne5 Nxe5 17. dxe5 Be7 18. Bd6 $1 $16 {Richard saved the game but definetely wasn't happy here.} Bxd6 19. exd6 Bd7 20. f3 exf3 21. Bxf3 Qa5 22. c5 b6 23. Bh5 Rxf1+ 24. Rxf1 Qxc5+ 25. Qxc5 bxc5 26. Rf7 Rd8 27. Re7 e5 28. g4 e4 29. Kf2 a5 30. h3 a4 31. bxa4 c4 32. a5 c3 33. Ke1 c5 34. a6 e3 35. Rxe3 d4 36. Re7 Bc6 37. a7 Rxd6 38. Re8+ Kg7 39. a8=Q Bxa8 40. Rxa8 d3 41. Ra7+ Kh6 42. exd3 Rxd3 43. Ra6+ Kg7 44. Ra7+ Kh6 {1/2-1/2 (44) Eljanov,P (2723)-Rapport,R (2671) Biel 2015}) 13. cxd5 (13. Ne5 $5 {Again some enginey flavour.} Ndxe5 14. dxe5 Bd7 {[%cal Gd8e8] If you enjoy signing below zeros maybe you would love to take on e5 and see what happens after white sacrifices on d5.} 15. f4 gxf4 $132 {[%cal Gf7h8,Gh8g6,Gg8h8,Gf8g8] Looks like a very healthy position in practice. In case of gxf4 we will gladly play Kh8-Rg8 remaining very solid and with many options like Nh6 to annoy our opponent. Against 16. Bxf5 Nh8!? could be fun to play but we need to be careful with Nxd5 ideas, so 16. ... Bg5 followed by 17. ... Qe7 might be wiser and safer. As a conclusion White needs to play a very schematic setup (g3) and then play like an engine. Well, this kind of players ofter prefer 2. Nc3 or more direct alternatives, so i'd be happy if they enter this territory of subtelties and precise piece moves.}) 13... cxd5 $132 {[%cal Gb7b6,Gc8a6] Taking with the c pawn is less punishing if White cannot use the c file nor the dark squares.½-½ (35) Wagner,D (2572)-Salem,A (2682) Biel 2021}) 11... dxe4 12. Ne5 {12. Ne1 Qe8!? and I'd be scared with white.} Nxe5 13. dxe5 Qc7 $1 $132 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gc6c5] We don't let White to play Rad1-Qc1. Now we'll take on e5 or go for c5 with enough space for our pieces and everything under reasonable control.}) 9... a5 {[%csl Ga8] Opening the a file looks reasonable for sure.} 10. a3 O-O 11. b4 (11. Bf4 Bf6 $5 {[%cal Gd7b6,Gg7g5] g5, Qe7, Nb6, we still have all the thematical moves available. Combining g5-Nd6-Qe7-Qg7 also looks very fancy and senseful.}) 11... axb4 12. axb4 Bf6 $132 {We control the Nf3-Ne5 jump and Nb6 is a serious threat. Feels difficult for White to pressure "easily" as we have plenty of resources with Ra3 and even some creative ideas with Rf7 going through the seventh rank.} (12... Nb6 13. c5 Nc4 $132 {[%cal Gc8d7,Gd7e8] Black isn't going too wrong here. Bd7-Be8 looks decent. 1/2-1/2 (37) Gombac,J (2246)-Rozic,S (2208) Slovenia 2019}) 13. c5 e5 $15 {Is the 219038128 example of how White tends to overestimate his chances facing the Dutch. Now Nxc3 and e5-e4 is so strong and black was ahead in ½-½ (43) Tunik,G (2384)-Volovich,V (2062) Voronezh 2017}) 8... Nd7 9. Bf4 {[%csl Ge5] Makes sense for White to keep the control of the e5 square.} (9. Nd3 $5 {This turns out to be a novelty. We don't like to take on c4 much often when our pawn is still on f5, so we are left without an obvious plan. Now I really love the following plan for White: an eventual e2-e3 and Qc2-b3-Bb2-Ne2, seizing the control of the e5 square. Also a very important detail is that we are not in time to play g5-g4 to prevent f2-f3 idea. Usually you don't see e2-e3 beeing played precisely for that reason. If we get to play g4 suddenly White would never be able to kick the e4 knight or even claim control of the square with exchanges.} Nb6 $1 {I prefer to change the pace. I don't want to allow white to have 20 free moves ahead.} (9... O-O 10. Qc2) 10. Nxe4 (10. c5 Nxc3 11. bxc3 Nc4 $132 {[%cal Gh7h5,Gh5h4,Yb7b6,Yc8a6] You can take the red pill (h5-h4) or the blue pill (b6 and try to control the c4 square).}) 10... fxe4 11. Ne5 Nd7 12. Bf4 O-O {And voilà! We Transposed to a more solid line, precisely the one White was trying to dodge :)}) (9. Nxd7 Bxd7 10. Nxe4 fxe4 11. f3 {White tries to be smart and prevent us from castling but we have both options still.} O-O $5 (11... exf3 12. Rxf3 dxc4 {This is a typical resource when white tries to kill our center.} 13. Qc2 Bf6 14. Qxc4 Qb6 15. Be3 Qxb2 $132 {Richard managed to get a playable position and was completely outplaying the opponent.} 16. Rff1 Qa3 17. Bd2 b5 18. Qc1 Bxd4+ 19. e3 Bb2 20. Qe1 Bxa1 21. Qxa1 Rf8 22. Rc1 Qd3 23. Bb4 Rf6 24. Kh1 Rd8 25. Qe5 Kf7 26. Qh5+ Kg8 27. Rd1 Qc2 28. Be7 Be8 29. Rxd8 {1-0 (29) Schneider,I (2487) -Rapport,R (2718) Austria 2014}) 12. fxe4 Rxf1+ $132 {[%cal Gd5c4,Yb7b5,Yd7e8] We'll take on c4 and look for b5-Be8. I enjoy positions where we have a very clear go-to and our opponents goals are not very clear.}) 9... O-O 10. Nxe4 (10. Qc2 {We find ourselves in a very popular position out of tranposition and black is doing great.} Nxe5 11. Bxe5 Nd6 $1 {[%cal Gd6c4] A theme usually seen in the Catalan with Bb4+, Be7 and eventually Ne4. We force the pawn exchange or taking a pawn. It has excellent results recently.} 12. b3 Nf7 $146 {[%cal Gf7e5,Gb7b6] This move is excellent and black equalizes comfortably. White exchanged his best knight and did not advance at all on the queenside.} (12... dxc4 $5 {I leave you a couple successfull examples on how this weird pawn sacrifice can work.} 13. e4 (13. Rad1 cxb3 14. axb3 Nf7 15. Bf4 Bg5 16. Bxg5 Qxg5 17. f4 Qh6 18. Na4 Rd8 19. Nb2 Qf6 20. e3 Nd6 21. Ra1 Bd7 22. Nd3 Be8 23. b4 a6 24. h3 Rac8 25. Kh2 Rc7 26. Ra5 Re7 27. Ne5 Nf7 28. Rd1 g5 29. Bf3 Qh6 30. Nd3 g4 31. Bg2 gxh3 32. Bf3 Nd6 33. Qe2 Rg7 34. Rg1 Qf6 35. Raa1 Bg6 36. Rac1 Kh8 37. Qf1 Rdg8 38. Qxh3 Qe7 39. Rg2 Ne8 40. Ne5 Qxb4 41. Qh4 Qf8 42. g4 fxg4 43. Rxg4 Nf6 44. Rg5 Be4 45. Rcg1 Bxf3 46. Nxf3 Ne4 47. Rxg7 Rxg7 48. Rxg7 Qxg7 49. Qd8+ Qg8 50. Qh4 a5 51. Nd2 Nxd2 {1/2-1/2 (51) Maghsoodloo,P (2721) -Sedlak,N (2472) Germany 2023}) 13... cxb3 14. Qxb3 Nf7 15. exf5 Nxe5 16. dxe5 Qb6 17. fxe6 Qxb3 18. axb3 Bxe6 19. Ne2 Bg4 20. Ra2 a5 21. h3 Bh5 22. Nf4 Bf7 23. e6 Be8 24. Rd1 g5 25. Nd3 Rf6 26. Re1 Bg6 27. Be4 Bf5 28. Bxf5 Rxf5 29. Ne5 Rf6 30. Nc4 Bb4 31. Re5 h6 32. Kg2 b5 33. Nb6 Re8 34. Rae2 Bd6 35. R5e4 Kg7 36. Nd7 Rf5 37. Rc2 c5 38. Rd2 Be7 39. Ne5 h5 40. Nc6 Bf6 41. Rd7+ Kg6 42. Nxa5 Bd4 43. f4 gxf4 44. gxf4 Rf6 45. Nc6 Bc3 46. Ne7+ Kh6 47. Nd5 Rg6+ 48. Kf1 Bd4 49. f5 Rg1+ 50. Ke2 Reg8 51. Nf4 Rb1 52. e7 Rb2+ 53. Kd3 Rg3+ {0-1 (54) Sargsyan,S (2602)-Martirosyan,H (2745) Almaty 2022}) 13. Bf4 b6 {[%cal Gc8a6,Ge7f6] Followed by Ba6 and then even g5 or Bf6. White has a silly knight on c3 and I don't see a way to make any progress.}) 10... fxe4 11. f3 {[%csl Rg2][%cal Gc8d7,Gd7e8] This looks promising for White but we are very solid. Our c8 bishop will shift to e8 and the g2 bishop is likely to have an existencial crisis soon enough facing the rock solid pawnchain.} Nxe5 12. Bxe5 exf3 13. exf3 {13. Rxf3 doesn't change much the movie.} Bf6 14. f4 (14. Re1 dxc4 {[%cal Gc8d7,Gd7e8] We shift the bishop through e8 and basically the isolated e6 pawn is balanced by the isolated d pawn.}) 14... Bxe5 15. dxe5 Bd7 $132 {[%cal Gd7e8,Ge8g6] Black is very solid. White has some space and definetely a claim could be made that white is better, but I see we have an easy plan and we have even some decent options through the d file if White gets too creative.} *

