[SourceVersionDate "2023.04.29"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. g3 Be7 (4... Bb4+ 5. Bd2 {Obviously you should also know 5. Nc3 and 5. Nbd2 but it is worth mentioning a couple ideas. Maybe you can play this move and have proper answers to Nc3-Nbd2 and then switch to Stonewall-like positions pretty confidently.} Be7 {This line is known for transpositions to the Dutch-style so it makes sense to talk about it briefly.} 6. Bg2 Ne4 $5 {This was also played by Rapport himself and the ideas are pretty similar. It's not a specially good move order as Bd2 is not that bad per se and i'd rather let White have the chance to play a passive b2-b3 or even Nbd2 so we can go for Nc6-h5 spicy ideas. 0-1 (43) Khotenashvili,B (2486) -Rapport,R (2700) Caleta 2018} (6... Nbd7 7. O-O c6 {This has been extensevely played by Sarana (current European Champion) and he chooses to play Ne4-f5 depending on what White plays. 7. ... Ne4 might be a bit smarter as this move order allows 8. Nc3 but friendly reminder i'm just telling you some guidelines so you can use the Stonewall knowledge.} 8. Qc2 Ne4 9. Bf4 g5 $5 {We have f7-f5 against everything to transpose to known territory but this move was recently played by Jorden Van Foorest and Eirigaisi and it can be a nice complement with your knowledge.} 10. Be3 Nd6 {[%cal Gd6f5,Yg5g4] And Nf5-g4 ideas are tricky to handle and we get a very spicy position.})) 5. Bg2 Ne4 {[%cal Gf7f5] I add this chapter to show you how this Dutch repertoire can even help you to face the mighty Catalan! As a Catalan Catalan player, I shouldn't be giving clues but it works very well! Funnily enough I was checking some lines of the Dutch and the same day I saw this beeing played to Parham (teammate) and felt it was a nice addition to the course.} 6. Ne5 $5 {We could obviously just go for 6. ... f5 but we can get a better version.} (6. O-O f5 {I'll add some games that came from the Catalan move order. Ivanisevic, for instance, has been playing it recently.} 7. Nc3 (7. Nbd2 Nc6 8. e3 h5 {[%cal Gh5h4] Ivanisevic already got a very pleasant and thematic position: 1-0 (44) Sjugirov,S (2675)-Ivanisevic,I (2604) Chess.com INT 2020}) 7... c6 8. Ne5 Nd7 9. Bf4 (9. Nxd7 Bxd7 10. Nxe4 fxe4 11. f3 exf3 12. Rxf3 dxc4 13. Qc2 Bf6 14. Qxc4 Qb6 15. Be3 Qxb2 16. Rff1 Qa3 17. Bd2 b5 $17 {1-0 (29) Schneider,I (2487) -Rapport,R (2718) Austria 2014}) 9... O-O 10. Qc2 Nxe5 11. Bxe5 Nd6 {We saw this line in another chapter, did you guess it came from a Catalan!?} 12. b3 dxc4 13. Rad1 cxb3 14. axb3 Nf7 15. Bf4 Bg5 16. Bxg5 Qxg5 17. f4 Qh6 18. Na4 Rd8 19. Nb2 Qf6 20. e3 Nd6 21. Ra1 Bd7 $132 {1/2-1/2 (51) Maghsoodloo,P (2721) -Sedlak,N (2472) Germany 2023}) (6. Nfd2 f5 $11) 6... O-O $5 {It is a bit smarter. As now we can go for f6 and then f5 to win a tempo.} 7. O-O f6 8. Nd3 (8. Nf3 f5 $11) 8... dxc4 {[%cal Ge4d6]} 9. Bxe4 Qxd4 $1 {And White is already in trouble!} *

