{[%evp 0,30,28,32,66,34,44,30,30,28,54,51,99,88,61,27,49,63,45,42,43,56,56,7,5,-63,-55,18,3,-3,1,-7,79] [#]} {Black to move} 4... g6 $1 5. h4 (5. Bf4 Bg7 6. e3 O-O 7. Nf3 d6 8. Be2 Nc6 $132 {[%cal Gd8e7,Gc6d8,Gd8f7] And we have a similar position covered in the London-ish approach to the Dutch, but with the extra a2-a3 played. Qe7-Nd8-Nf7 was the chosen plan.}) (5. Nf3 Bg7 6. g3 d6 7. Bg2 O-O 8. O-O Ne4 $132 {e7-e6 is far more useful than a2-a3. We'll end up playing Nxc3 and e5 and we get an excellent Leningrad.}) (5. e3 $5 {White can readjust now that we go for the Leningrad approach. Be2-b4-Bb2 is definetely a dangerous setup, still to be discovered.} b6 $5 {We create some concrete threats to annoy our opponent.} 6. Be2 Bb7 {[%csl Rg2]} 7. Bf3 d5 {[%cal Gc7c6,Gd8d7,Gf8d6] We have a very interesting Stonewall where White might have some troubles readjusting his pieces.}) 5... d6 {We prevent h4-h5 calmly.} (5... Bg7 6. h5 Nxh5 7. e4 $16 {[%cal Gh1h5]} Nf6 8. e5 $1 $18 {That's why 5. ... d6 is useful.}) 6. e3 Bg7 {We do a final "bait" for h4-h5.} 7. Be2 h6 $132 {[%csl Gg4][%cal Ge6e5] We'll end up playing e5 eventually and we have the g4 square for the knight in the future.} *

