{[%evp 0,30,28,24,69,49,49,49,50,48,63,63,64,78,66,71,66,38,41,36,35,29,51,40,40,40,47,41,52,60,51,54,59] [#]} {Black to move} 11... Ne4 {[%cal Gb7b6]} (11... b6 $2 12. cxd5 $16 {[%csl Gc6][%cal Gc1c6,Yc6e6,Yc6a8]}) 12. Nb1 Qf6 $5 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Ge6e5,Gd5c4] We need to consider this move order for White as very tricky (always having the c6 square in sight to prevent b7-b6. This move has some interesting ideas, for instance allowing b7-b6 as cxd5 exd5! and the c6 pawn would be defended by the queen. We also pave the road to play dxc4-e5 ideas. e3 or Rd1 are faced with e5! and black is more than fine.} (12... dxc4 {This is also a very creative approach, that can help you in similar positions. But I prefer in general to avoid opening the position and leaving us with the f5 pawn.} 13. Qxc4 (13. bxc4 e5 $132 {[%csl Rb7,Gc5,Rc6,Rg2] Would be great for black.}) 13... Nb6 {[%cal Ge6e5]} 14. Qc2 e5 15. dxe5 Qxe5 16. Nd2 $14 {[%csl Gf5]}) *

